p31               = Validei Atik\n|p32               = Yavuzt\u00fcrk\n|p33               = Zeynep Kamil\n<!-- government type, leaders -->\n|government_footnotes = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n|government_type   = \n|leader_party      = [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AKP]]\n|leader_title      = Mayor\n|leader_name       = Hilmi T\u00fcrkmen\n|leader_title1     = \n|leader_name1      = <!-- etc., up to leader_title4 / leader_name4 -->\n<!-- display settings  --------->\n|total_type        = <!-- to set a non-standard label for total area and population rows -->\n|unit_pref         = <!-- enter: Imperial, to display imperial before metric -->\n|area_footnotes   = {{Turkey district areas|SOURCE}}\n|area_blank1_title= District\n|area_blank1_km2  = {{Turkey district areas|\u0130stanbul|\u00dcsk\u00fcdar}}\n|elevation_m      = \n|population_footnotes    = [https://www.nufusu.com/ilce/uskudar_istanbul-nufusu 2]\n|population_as_of        = 2018\n|population_blank1_title = District\n|population_blank1       = 529,145\n|population_density_blank1_km2  = auto\n<!-- demographics (section 1) -->\n|demographics_type1      = \n|demographics1_footnotes = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n|demographics1_title1    = \n|demographics1_info1     = <!-- etc., up to demographics1_title5 / demographics1_info5 -->\n\n<!-- demographics (section 2) -->\n|demographics_type2      = \n|demographics2_footnotes = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n|demographics2_title1    = \n|demographics2_info1     = <!-- etc., up to demographics2_title5 / demographics2_info5 -->\n\n<!-- time zone(s) -------------->\n|timezone1               = \n|utc_offset1             = \n|timezone1_DST           = \n|utc_offset1_DST         = \n|timezone2               = \n|utc_offset2             = \n|timezone2_DST           = \n|utc_offset2_DST         =\n\n<!-- postal codes, area code --->\n|postal_code_type        = <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal_code             = \n|postal2_code_type       = <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal2_code            = \n|area_code_type          = <!-- defaults to: Area code(s) -->\n|area_code               =\n\n<!-- twin cities --------------->\n|twin1                   = [[Shibuya, Tokyo|Shibuya]]\n|twin1_country           = Japan\n|twin2                   = [[Kemah, Turkey|Kemah]]\n|twin2_country           = [[Turkey]]\n|twin3                   = [[Bakhchisaray]]\n|twin3_country           = [[Ukraine]]\n|twin4                   = [[G\u00f6yn\u00fck]]\n|twin4_country           = [[Turkey]]\n<!-- website, footnotes -------->\n|website                 = {{url|uskudar.bel.tr}}\n|footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''\u00dcsk\u00fcdar''' ({{IPA-tr|ys\u02c8cyda\u027e}}), traditionally known in Italian and English as '''Scutari''' ({{transl|el|Skout\u00e0rion}}, {{lang|el|\u03a3\u03ba\u03bf\u03c5\u03c4\u03ac\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03bd}} in [[Greek language|Greek]]), and in [[classical antiquity]] known as '''Chrysopolis''' (Greek: \u03a7\u03c1\u03c5\u03c3\u03cc\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c2, 'Golden City'), is a large and densely populated district and municipality of [[Istanbul]], [[Turkey]], on the [[Anatolia]]n shore of the [[Bosphorus]]. It is bordered on the north by [[Beykoz]], on the east by [[\u00dcmraniye]], on the southeast by [[Ata\u015fehir]], on the south by [[Kad\u0131k\u00f6y]], and on the west by the Bosphorus, with the areas of [[Be\u015fikta\u015f]], [[Beyo\u011flu]], and [[Emin\u00f6n\u00fc]] on the opposite shore.<!-- new boundaries of Uskudar http://www.ibb.gov.tr/tr-TR/Pages/Haber.aspx?NewsID=15773 --> It is home to about half a million people. \u00dcsk\u00fcdar is also the usual name for the historic center of the municipality.\n\n==Etymology==\n{{lang|tr|\u00dcsk\u00fcdar|italic=no}} was originally called {{lang|grc-Latn|Skoutarion}} ([[Byzantine Greek]]: {{lang|grc|\u03a3\u03ba\u03bf\u03c5\u03c4\u03ac\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03bd}}) during the [[Byzantine Empire]]. This word may have been used to describe the {{lang|la|[[scutum (shield)|scutum]]}} shields that guards used that were made of leather. This is believed because the word ''scutari'' means 'raw tanned leather'. Others{{who|date=November 2019}} who visited the area called it {{lang|und-Latn|Eks\u00fcdar}} or {{lang|fr|Escutaire}}.<ref name=\"WDL2\">{{cite serial |url=http://www.wdl.org/en/item/8823/ |title=Mosque and Street, Scutari, Constantinople, Turkey |website=[[World Digital Library]] |year=1890\u20131900 |accessdate=18 October 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Chrysopolis===\n\u00dcsk\u00fcdar was founded in the 7th century BC by [[Ancient Greeks|ancient Greek]] colonists from [[Megara]] as ''Chrysopolis'' ({{lang-grc-gre|\u03a7\u03c1\u03c5\u03c3\u03cc\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c2}}, 'Golden City'), a few decades before [[Byzantium]] was founded on the opposite shore.<ref name=\"Taylor\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MQRNMc0wgMgC&pg=PA219|title=Imperial Istanbul: A Traveler's Guide|first=Jane|last=Taylor|date=13 October 1998|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|accessdate=16 May 2018|via=Google Books}}</ref> According to an ancient Greek geographer, the city received the name Chrysopolis because the [[Persian empire]] had a gold depository there or because it was associated with [[Agamemnon]] and [[Chryseis]]' son, Chryses.<ref name=\"Smith\">William Smith.''[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0064:id=chrysopolis-geo Dictionary of Greek and Roman Geography \u2014 \"Chryso'polis\"]'' 1854.</ref> On the other hand, according to an 18th-century writer, it received the name because of the excellence of its harbor.<ref>{{cite book|author=Fran\u00e7ois Sabbathier|title= Dictionnaire pour l'intelligence des auteurs classiques, grecs et latins: tants sacr\u00e9s que profanes, contenant la g\u00e9ographie, l'histoire, la fable, et les antiquit\u00e9s|date=1772|volume=11|page=135|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jOE1AAAAMAAJ&d}}</ref> The city was used as a harbor and shipyard and was an important staging post in the wars between the Greeks and Persians. In 410 BC Chrysopolis was taken by the Athenian general [[Alcibiades]], and the Athenians used it thenceforth to charge a toll on ships coming from and going to the Black Sea.<ref name=\"Smith\"/> Long overshadowed by its neighbor [[Chalcedon]] during the Hellenistic and Roman period, it maintained its identity and increased its prosperity until it surpassed Chalcedon.<ref name=\"Taylor\"/> Due to its less favorable location with respect to the currents of the Bosporus, however, it never surpassed Byzantium.<ref name=\"Taylor\"/>\n\nIn AD 324, the [[Battle of Chrysopolis|final battle]] between [[Constantine the Great|Constantine I]], Emperor of the West, and [[Licinius]], Emperor of the East, in which Constantine defeated Licinius, took place at Chrysopolis.<ref name=\"Taylor\"/> When Constantine made Byzantium his capital, Chrysopolis, together with Chalcedon, became suburbs.<ref name=\"Taylor\"/> Chrysopolis remained important throughout the Byzantine period because all trade routes to Asia started there, and all Byzantine army units headed to Asia mustered there.<ref name=\"Taylor\"/>\nDuring the brief usurpation of the Armenian general [[Artabasdos]], his eldest son, [[Niketas (son of Artabasdos)|Niketas]], was defeated with his [[Byzantine army|forces]] at Chrysopolis by the army of [[Constantine V]], before Artabasdos was finally deposed by the legitimate emperor Constantine and blinded. For this reason, and because of its location across from [[Constantinople]], it was a natural target for anyone aiming at the capital.<ref name=\"Taylor\"/> Also, in the 8th century AD it was taken by a small band of Arabs, who caused considerable destruction and panic in Constantinople, before withdrawing.<ref name=\"Taylor\"/> In 988, a rebellion that nearly toppled [[Basil II]] began in Chrysopolis, before he was able to crush with the aid of [[Varangian Guard|Russian mercenaries]].<ref name=\"Taylor\"/>\n\n===Skoutarion, Scutari===\n[[File:12_-_Konstantinopel%3B_Scheda-Karte_europ_T\u00fcrkei.jpg|thumb|left|Under the Ottomans, Scutari was a large neighborhood with many cemeteries, across the water from [[Constantinople]] (map by [[Joseph von Scheda]], 1860\u201370]]\nIn the 12th century, the city changed its name to ''Skoutarion'' ({{lang-el|\u03a3\u03ba\u03bf\u03c5\u03c4\u03ac\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03bd}}), the name deriving from the Emperor's Skoutarion Palace nearby.<ref name=\"Taylor\"/> In 1338 the Ottoman leader [[Orhan Gazi]] took Skoutarion, giving the Ottomans a base within sight of Constantinople for the first time.<ref name=\"Taylor\"/>\n\nIn the Ottoman period \u00dcsk\u00fcdar was one of the three communities outside the city walls of Constantinople (along with [[Ey\u00fcp]] and [[Galata]]). The area was a major burial ground, and today many large cemeteries remain, including Karacaahmet Mezarl\u0131\u011f\u0131, B\u00fclb\u00fclderesi Mezarl\u0131\u011f\u0131, and a number of Jewish and Christian cemeteries. Karacaahmet Mezarl\u0131\u011f\u0131 is one of Istanbul's largest cemeteries. The B\u00fclb\u00fclderesi cemetery is next to Fevziye Hatun mosque.<ref>Soner Yal\u00e7\u0131n. ''Efendi''.</ref>\n\nThe neighborhood suffered during the ethnic-religious violence of the 6 September 1955, [[Istanbul pogrom]]. Shops were looted, women raped, and many Greeks and Armenians left.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780974766034|url-access=registration|title=The Mechanism of Catastrophe: The Turkish Pogrom of September 6\u20137, 1955, and the Destruction of the Greek Community of Istanbul|publisher=greekworks.com|first=Speros|last=Vryonis|date=1 January 2005|website=Greekworks.com|accessdate=16 May 2018|via=Internet Archive|isbn=978-0-9747660-3-4}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Mills|first=Amy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IHyA1DCtsnUC&pg=PA119|title=Streets of Memory: Landscape, Tolerance, and National Identity in Istanbul|publisher=The University of Georgia Press|date=2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Pamuk|first=Orhan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KTE7DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA278|title=Istanbul: Memories and the City|publisher=Alfred A. Knopf|date=2005}}</ref>\n\n==\u00dcsk\u00fcdar today==\n\n{{Update-section|date=January 2019}}\n[[File:K\u0131zkulesinden \u00dcsk\u00fcdar.jpg|right|thumb|The waterfront of \u00dcsk\u00fcdar as seen from [[Maiden's Tower|Maiden Tower]]]]\nThe district of \u00dcsk\u00fcdar is one of Istanbul's oldest-established residential areas. It is directly opposite the old city of [[Emin\u00f6n\u00fc]] and transport across the Bosphorus is easy by boat or bridge. So there are well-established communities here, many retired people, and many residents commute to the European side for work or school (being cheap and central \u00dcsk\u00fcdar has a large student population). During the rush-hour, the waterfront is bustling with people running from ferryboats and motorboats onto buses and minibuses. \u00dcsk\u00fcdar also has the smell of the sea, the sound of foghorns, motorboats and seagulls and one of the best views of the city.\n\n[[File:Uskudar Square.jpg|right|thumb|Central \u00dcsk\u00fcdar on a snowy day, with [[Mihrimah Sultan Mosque (\u00dcsk\u00fcdar)|Mihrimah Sultan Mosque]] in the background]]\n{{As of|2006}}, the central square is being dug up for a tunnel under the Bosphorus which will carry an underground railway. However, this is predictably continuously running into artifacts of great archaeological value.\n\nThe area behind the ferry dock is a busy shopping district, with many restaurants (including the well-known ''Kanaat Lokantas\u0131'' serving Ottoman cuisine, [[olive oil]]-based dishes, and ice cream) and a number of important Ottoman mosques (see section below). However, there are relatively few cafes, cinemas, billiard halls, and places for youth to congregate.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}\n\nThe private [[\u00dcsk\u00fcdar University]], founded by the [[Human Values and Mental Health Foundation]], has a campus here.\n\nUskudar has two public libraries: [[\u015eemsi Pasha Mosque]] Public Library (built in 1953) and Selimiye Public Library.\n\n==Neighborhoods==\n\n[[File:Uskudar fountain.jpg|right|thumb|Sultan [[Ahmet III]] Fountain in \u00dcsk\u00fcdar square]]\n\n\u00dcsk\u00fcdar is a municipality within borders of Istanbul Metropolitan Municipality ({{lang|tr|[[b\u00fcy\u00fck\u015fehir belediyeleri|b\u00fcy\u00fck\u015fehir]]}}). The municipality is subdivided into neighborhoods ({{lang|tr|[[mahalle]]ler}}). The boundaries and names of the official neighborhoods change from time to time and sometimes do not correspond to historically recognized neighborhoods or to residents' own perceptions.\n\nThe most prominent neighborhood is \u00dcsk\u00fcdar's historic center ({{lang|tr|merkez}}), centered on the ferry docks and roughly corresponding to the current Mimar Sinan neighborhood (former Selmana\u011fa, Tembel Hac\u0131 Mehmet, and \u0130nk\u0131lap neighborhoods). This area includes large historic mosques, many businesses and markets, and is a transportation hub.\n\nOther prominent neighborhoods include the former villages on the Bosphorus to the north of the historic center, Kuzguncuk, Beylerbeyi, \u00c7engelk\u00f6y, Kuleli, Vanik\u00f6y (now part of Kandilli), and Kandilli; the neighborhoods along the Bosphorus shore south of the historic center, [[Salacak]], [[Harem, Istanbul|Harem]] (now part of Aziz Mahmud Huday\u0131), and Selimiye; and the mostly residential neighborhoods on the hilltops and hillsides, Do\u011fanc\u0131lar (now mostly part of Aziz Mahmud Huday\u0131), \u0130mrahor (now part of Salacak), Selams\u0131z (now part of Selamiali), Ba\u011flarba\u015f\u0131 (now part of Altunizade), Altunizade, Ac\u0131badem, K\u00fc\u00e7\u00fck \u00c7aml\u0131ca, and B\u00fcy\u00fck \u00c7aml\u0131ca (mostly in K\u0131s\u0131kl\u0131, Burhaniye, and Ferah).\n\n===Salacak===\n\u00dcsk\u00fcdar's long promenade along the coast from the center down in southern direction towards the bus station at [[Harem, Istanbul|Harem]] is popular in summer as it commands views of the European shore of [[Topkap\u0131 Palace]], [[Hagia Sophia|Aya Sofya]], [[Sultan Ahmed Mosque]] (The [[Sultan Ahmed Mosque|Blue Mosque]]), [[Taksim Square|Taksim]] and [[Be\u015fikta\u015f]]. This promenade is lined with cafes and restaurants, the most prominent of which is not on the coast but out in the water: the [[Maiden's Tower]] ({{lang|tr|K\u0131z Kulesi}}), a small tower just off the coast that has existed since [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] times, when it was called Leander's Tower. From time to time it has been used as a toll booth; now it is used as an upscale restaurant and a venue for wedding parties. The name comes from a legend about a princess shut in the tower.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}\n\nOn nice days people gather on the shore to fish, sit and drink tea or to enjoy being out on the water in little rowing boats. There is a more recent mosque (1760) on the shore opposite the tower. The streets of Salacak behind the coast, in the area called ''Imrahor'', are attractive and still hold a number of classic Ottoman wooden houses. The legendary 17th-century [[Hezarfen Ahmet \u00c7elebi]] is said to have landed here on his hang-glider flight across the Bosphorus.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}\n\nFurther down along the coast is the Harem neighborhood, which contains a major intercity bus terminal and the [[Selimiye Barracks]], where [[Florence Nightingale]] once tended wounded British soldiers.<ref name=\"WDL\">{{cite serial |url = http://www.wdl.org/en/item/8822/ |title = Cypresses and Road Leading to the Cemetery, Scutari, Constantinople, Turkey |website = [[World Digital Library]]|year = 1890\u20131900|accessdate = 18 October 2013}}</ref> Behind the coast, towards the east, \u00dcsk\u00fcdar climbs steeply into the residential areas uphill, Ba\u011flarba\u015f\u0131 and Do\u011fanc\u0131lar.\n\n===Do\u011fanc\u0131lar===\nA pleasant neighborhood on the hill above Salacak, with plenty of trees between the buildings and a small park. There is a wide avenue winding uphill from \u00dcsk\u00fcdar, which has plenty of shops and cafes, and also a theater (the Musahipzade Celal Sahnesi), the fire station, the former women's prison ([[Pa\u015fakap\u0131s\u0131 Prison]]), Burhan Felek High School and Do\u011fanc\u0131lar mosque (opposite the park).\n\n===Ba\u011flarba\u015f\u0131 and Altunizade===\n[[File:Altunizade Mosque.jpg|thumb|right|[[Altunizade Mosque]]]]\nFormerly orchards and fruit-gardens ({{lang|tr|ba\u011f}}), it became a residential neighborhood in the 19th century, home to the typical Istanbul urban mix of Greeks, Jews, Turks, and Armenians.{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}} The neighborhood still has an Armenian school and the Armenian church of Surp Garabed, built in 1844. Until the 1990s the area remained a middle-class residential neighborhood,{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}} and today is still an attractive district with a mixture of housing and office/commercial property. A number of properties have been converted to office and business use. Altunizade is still an attractive residential neighborhood, home to the large and busy Capitol shopping and entertainment center. Altunizade was established in the early 19th century by [[Altunizade \u0130smail Z\u00fcht\u00fc Pasha]]. He also commissioned [[Altunizade Mosque]], which was built in 1866.\n\nThere are a number of well-known schools within the district including [[\u00dcsk\u00fcdar American Academy]], one of the oldest established schools in the city, \u00dcsk\u00fcdar High School, a state school, Haydarpasha High School, [[Marmara University]]'s faculty of theology; and Burhan Felek sports complex.\n\n===Selams\u0131z===\n[[Selams\u0131z]] is an old residential neighborhood, home to a [[Romani people|Roma]] (Gypsy) community and Roma culture.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}\n\n===Ac\u0131badem===\nThe top half of the attractive district of [[Ac\u0131badem, Kad\u0131k\u00f6y|Ac\u0131badem]] also belongs to \u00dcsk\u00fcdar, including Ac\u0131badem and Academic hospitals. This avenue with its [[patisserie]]s, ice-cream parlors and caf\u00e9s, is the center one of the most pleasant neighborhoods of Istanbul,{{fact|date=March 2019}} consisting of tree-lined streets and well-planned housing areas, as well as \u00c7aml\u0131ca Girls\u2019 High School set in a tree-lined garden.{{fact|date=March 2019}}\n\n===Up the Bosphorus===\nThe boundary of the municipality of \u00dcsk\u00fcdar is far up the Bosphorus, and beyond lies [[Beykoz]]. \u00dcsk\u00fcdar's up-north Bosphorus villages include:\n\n====Pa\u015faliman\u0131====\nJust past \u00dcsk\u00fcdar the coastline is called Pa\u015faliman\u0131. ''Liman'' means \"port\" in Turkish (from [[Greek language|Greek]] {{lang|el|lim\u00e0ni}}, {{lang|el|\u03bb\u03b9\u03bc\u03ac\u03bd\u03b9}}) and boats would moor here. A large stone building on the shore, built as a tobacco warehouse by late-Ottoman architect Vedat Tek, has been completely renovated and now serves as headquarters of [[List of power companies of Turkey|Ciner Grubu]] ([[Ciner Group]]), an industrial conglomerate. There is a small area of parkland right on the shore and the entrance to the large Fetih Pa\u015fa Korusu park is here.\n\n====Kuzguncuk====\nA Bosphorus village of streets with little shops, seaside cafes, and many old-fashioned wooden houses, [[Kuzguncuk]] has a village atmosphere. There is a ferry dock and a little park on the waterfront. The village was called ''Kosinitsa'' in the Byzantine period and until recently the people of Kuzguncuk were the typical Istanbul cosmopolitan mixture of Turks, Greeks, Jews, and Armenians.{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}} There are very few non-Muslims left today and the area has become an attractive middle-class neighborhood, home to people like film director [[U\u011fur Y\u00fccel]], sculptor [[Kuzgun Acar]], painter [[Acar Ba\u015fkut]] (whose studio is in the village), architects [[Nevzat Sayin]] and [[Cengiz Bekta\u015f]], and the late poet [[Can Y\u00fccel]]. The neighborhood is also portrayed in the novel ''Mediterranean Waltz'' (Kumral Ada Mavi Tuna) by [[Buket Uzuner]].\n\n====Beylerbeyi====\nJust beyond the [[Bosphorus bridge]] is [[Beylerbeyi]], an area known in Istanbul for its fish restaurants, and for the Ottoman palace on the shore. The [[Sabanc\u0131 family]] of Turkish industrialists have sponsored the restoration and building of the school, police station and other public buildings, thus making them appropriate to the many very attractive houses and shops in the village.\n\n====\u00c7engelk\u00f6y====\nFormerly a waterfront village, known for the cucumbers grown in gardens on the green hillsides behind. There are a number of very grand seaside villas ({{lang|tr|[[yal\u0131]]}}). The village has a number of shops, bakeries and waterfront cafes offering gorgeous views of the Bosphorus that tend to be busy, especially at weekends. Since the mid-1990s new housing estates have been built on the hillsides and now there are always queues of traffic through \u00c7engelk\u00f6y. But the village retains some of its romantic charm. The word {{lang|tr|\u00e7engel}} means \"hook\" or \"anchor\" in Turkish, and {{lang|tr|k\u00f6y}} means \"village\"; apparently there were blacksmiths or metalworkers in the village in Ottoman times.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}\n\nThe highly prestigious [[Kuleli Military High School]] is on the Bosphorus just beyond \u00c7engelk\u00f6y. Most graduates from here go on to military academy and careers as army officers.\n\n===Inland from the center of \u00dcsk\u00fcdar===\n\n====\u00c7aml\u0131ca====\nThis hill, known as ''Tchamlidja'' in 19th-century spelling, has the highest point in Istanbul and commands a panoramic view of the entire city. One of the most prestiged schools of Turkey, Bilfen College is located on the \u00c7aml\u0131ca hill.\n\n<!-- Ko\u015fuyolu is in fact now part of Kad\u0131k\u00f6y. Was it once part of \u00dcsk\u00fcdar?\n====Ko\u015fuyolu====\nA quiet residential district, with some well-known hospitals in parkland going back to the Ottoman period.-->\n\n==Sights of \u00dcsk\u00fcdar==\n[[File:Yeni Valide Mosque-2.jpg|thumb| [[Yeni Valide Camii]], the \"New Mosque\" of the [[mother sultan]]]]\n\nThough densely populated, \u00dcsk\u00fcdar has many areas of greenery, including the \u00c7aml\u0131ca hills, the Bosphorus coastline, and various parks. In addition, the area has a high concentration of historic buildings and religious sites.\n\n===Parks===\n[[Fethi Pa\u015fa Korusu]] is a large park on the hillside that extends down to the Bosphorus shore, slightly beyond \u00dcsk\u00fcdar in the area called Pa\u015faliman\u0131. It is named after [[Fetih Ahmet Pa\u015fa]] an Ottoman prince who among other things was responsible for industrializing the [[glassworks]] of Ottoman Turkey, and had a home in the area. The parkland is in fact privately owned and let to the state on condition that it is preserved as a park. The owners are the estate of Turkish industrialist [[Nuri Demira\u011f]]. There is a caf\u00e9 in the park, a stone waterfall which children climb on and a small stage area where on Friday evenings in summer a band of amateur musicians give open-air concerts at sunset. At weekends the young lovers of \u00dcsk\u00fcdar gather here to stroll and cuddle in the shade.{{fact|date=March 2019}}\n\n===Mosques===\n[[File:\u00c7inili Mosque.jpg|right|thumb|\u00c7inili (Tiled) Mosque]]\n[[File:Namazg\u00e2h Mosque.jpg|right|thumb|The wooden [[Namazg\u00e2h Mosque]]]]\n\u00dcsk\u00fcdar is home to over 180 mosques,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uskudarmuftulugu.gov.tr/index.php?makaleid=77 |title=Archived copy |access-date=10 August 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008104913/http://www.uskudarmuftulugu.gov.tr/index.php?makaleid=77 |archive-date=2011-10-08 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> many of them historic Ottoman buildings, many built for women of the imperial harem, and many built by the architect [[Mimar Sinan]]. Among the first things one sees on arriving by ferry are the two mosques on either side of the ferry port, both designed by Sinan. The larger one is the [[Mihrimah Sultan Mosque (\u00dcsk\u00fcdar)|Mihrimah Sultan Mosque]], sometimes called the \u0130skele (Dock) Mosque, built by a daughter of [[Suleiman the Magnificent]]; the smaller one is the [[\u015eemsi Pasha Mosque]], built by a [[vizier]] of Suleiman's. \u015eemsi Pasha has a small library building in the courtyard where one can sit and enjoy the sea breeze off the Bosphorus.\n\nA little further inland between the fountain of Ahmet III and the \u015eemsi Pasha Mosque is the large [[Yeni Valide Mosque]], built by Ahmet III's mother. Uphill from the dock in the Valideiatik neighborhood is the [[Atik Valide Mosque]], built by Murat III's mother and also designed by Sinan. Further uphill from there is the smaller [[\u00c7inili Mosque|\u00c7inili (Tiled) Mosque]]. In [[Karacaahmet Cemetery]] is the large [[\u015eakirin Mosque]], built in 2009.\n\nThe [[Namazg\u00e2h Mosque]] (built in 1860) in the eastern part of \u00dcsk\u00fcdar, close to the border with [[\u00dcmraniye]], is one of the few historical wooden mosques in Istanbul.\n\nOther important mosques of \u00dcsk\u00fcdar include<!-- list from Istanbul Inanc Atlasi --> Ahmediye, Ahmet A\u011fa, Ahmet \u00c7elebi, Altunizade, Ayazma, Aziz Mahmut Hudai, Baki Efendi, Beylerbeyi, Bodrumi \u00d6mer L\u00fctfi Efendi, Bostanc\u0131, Bulgurlu, \u00c7ak\u0131rc\u0131ba\u015f\u0131, Fatih, G\u00fclfem Hatun, Hac\u0131 \u00d6mer, \u0130mrahor, \u0130ranl\u0131lar, \u0130stavroz, Kandilli, Kara Davut Pasha, Kaymak Mustafa Pasha, K\u0131s\u0131kl\u0131, K\u00fcleli Bah\u00e7e, Malatyal\u0131 \u0130smail A\u011fa, Mirzazade, Pa\u015faliman\u0131, Rum Mehmet Pasha, Selimiye, Solak Sinan, Tah\u0131r Efendi, \u00dcryanizade, and Vanikoy.\n\n===Churches===\n[[File:Surp Krikor Lusavori\u00e7 Armenian Church.jpg|thumb|right|The Surp Krikor Lusavori\u00e7 (St [[Gregory the Illuminator]]) Armenian Church]]\nChurches of \u00dcsk\u00fcdar include <!-- list from municipal web site http://www.uskudar.bel.tr/portal/rehber_/rehbern.jsp?PageName=rehbern&ID=10404&ADI=Kiliseler --> the \u0130lya Profiti (Prophet Elijah) Greek Orthodox Church in Muratreis (present building built in 1831), the Kandilli Khristos Rum Ortodoks Kilisesi (built in 1810), the Surp Garabet (Saint John the Baptist) Armenian Church in Murat Reis (first church on the site, 1590; present building built 1888), the Surp Ha\u00e7 (Holy Cross) Armenian Church in Selami Ali (built 1676, rebuilt 1880), the Surp Krikor Lusavori\u00e7 (Saint Gregory the Illuminator) Armenian Church in Kuzguncuk (first built 1835, rebuilt 1861), and the Surp Yergodasan Arakelots (Twelve Apostoles) Armenian Church in Kandilli (built 1846).<ref>\u00dcsk\u00fcdar Belediyesi. ''Kiliseler''. {{cite web |url=http://www.uskudar.bel.tr/portal/rehber_/rehbern.jsp?PageName=rehbern&ID=10404&ADI=Kiliseler |title=Archived copy |accessdate=22 November 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006122648/http://www.uskudar.bel.tr/portal/rehber_/rehbern.jsp?PageName=rehbern&ID=10404&ADI=Kiliseler |archivedate=6 October 2011 |df= }} Retrieved 14 August 2009</ref><ref>Tu\u011flac\u0131, pages 121\u2013129, 169\u2013171, 194.</ref>\n\n===Synagogues===\nSynagogues of \u00dcsk\u00fcdar include <!-- list from chief rabbinate http://www.musevicemaati.com/index.php?contentId=27 --> [[Bet Yaakov Synagogue|Bet Yaakov]] (built 1878) and [[Bet Nissim Synagogue|Bet Nissim]] (built in the 1840s).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musevicemaati.com/index.php?contentId=27|title=Alan Ad\u0131na Ait Varsay\u0131lan Sayfa|website=Musevicemaati.com|accessdate=16 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Other religious buildings===\nImportant [[khanqah|''tekke''s]] ([[dervish]] lodges) include the [[Aziz Mahmud Hudayi]] Tekke (Aziz Mahmud Hudayi (1541\u20131628), who is buried in \u00dcsk\u00fcdar and was the founder of the [[Jelveti]] [[Sufi]] order){{Citation needed|date=September 2009}}; the Nasuhi Efendi Tekke (Nasuhi Efendi was the founder of the Nasuhiyye [[Khalwati order|Khalwati]] [[Sufi]] order {{Citation needed|date=September 2009}} and the grandfather of the Turkish-American music producer [[Ahmet Erteg\u00fcn]]); and the \u00d6zbekler Tekkesi, where the Erteg\u00fcn family members are buried.\n\nImportant tombs in \u00dcsk\u00fcdar include<!-- list from Istanbul Inanc Atlasi --> those of Aziz Mahmud Hudayi, Hac\u0131 Ahmet Pasha, Halil Pasha, [[\u0130brahim Edhem Pasha]], Karaca Ahmet, and Rum Mehmet Pasha.\n\n==={{lang|tr|\u00c7e\u015fme}}s and {{lang|tr|sebil}}s===\nOther notable Ottoman features to be seen in \u00dcsk\u00fcdar are the many ''{{linktext|\u00e7e\u015fme|lang=tr}}''s (drinking water sources) and ''{{linktext|sebil|lang=tr}}''s (kiosks for distribution of drinks). One of the largest and most visible {{lang|tr|\u00e7e\u015fme}}s is the fountain of [[Ahmet III]] (1728\u201329), an impressive marble structure in the center of \u00dcsk\u00fcdar near the ferry docks.\n\nOther important {{lang|tr|\u00e7e\u015fme}}s of \u00dcsk\u00fcdar include G\u00fclnu\u015f Emetullah Valide Sultan (1709, next to the Yeni Valide Mosque), H\u00fcseyin Avni Pasha (1874, Pa\u015faliman\u0131), [[Mustafa III]] (1760, next to the Ayazma Mosque), and [[Selim III]] (1802, in \u00c7i\u00e7ek\u00e7i, Harem \u0130skelesi Street).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kultur.gov.tr/TR/BelgeGoster.aspx?F6E10F8892433CFFA79D6F5E6C1B43FF856F72A66C829B67 |title=Archived copy |access-date=10 August 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070228010047/http://www.kultur.gov.tr/TR/BelgeGoster.aspx?F6E10F8892433CFFA79D6F5E6C1B43FF856F72A66C829B67 |archive-date=2007-02-28 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nImportant {{lang|tr|sebil}}s of \u00dcsk\u00fcdar include <!-- list from Istanbul Sebilleri -->those of Hac\u0131 H\u00fcseyin Pasha (1865, near the [[Karacaahmet Cemetery]]), Halil Pasha (1617, attached to [[Halil Pasha]]'s tomb), Hudayi (first built in the 1590s but later much remodeled, near [[Aziz Mahmud Hudayi]]'s tomb), Sadettin Efendi (1741, near the tomb of Karacaahmet Cemetery), [[\u015eeyh\u00fclislam]] Arif Hikmet Bey (1858, near the Kartal Baba Mosque), Valide \u00c7inili (1640, next to the \u00c7inili Mosque), Valide-i Cedid (1709, next to the Yeni Valide Mosque), and Ziya Bey (1866, near the tomb of Karacaahmet).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uskudar-bld.gov.tr/portal/rehber_/t1.jsp?PageName=main&RehberGrpId=8 |title=Archived copy |access-date=10 August 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090830184630/http://www.uskudar-bld.gov.tr/portal/rehber_/t1.jsp?PageName=main |archive-date=2009-08-30 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Museums===\n<!-- no useful official list of museums; used http://www.istanbul.net.tr/istanbul_muzeler.asp -->\nThe [[Florence Nightingale Museum (Istanbul)|Florence Nightingale Museum]] inside the [[Selimiye Barracks]] in Selimiye displays items associated with [[Florence Nightingale|Nightingale]] and her medical work in Istanbul during the [[Crimean War]].<ref>{{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Scutari (Turkey) |display=Scutari |volume=24 |page=518}}</ref> The [[Beylerbeyi Palace]] Museum in [[Beylerbeyi]] shows the palace built for [[Abd\u00fclaziz]] in the 1860s.\n\n==Education==\n* [[\u00dcsk\u00fcdar American Academy]] (formerly American Academy for Girls)\n* [[Tarabya British Schools]] has its [[\u00c7engelk\u00f6y]] campus there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tarabyabritishschools.com/contact-us|title=Contact Us|publisher=[[Tarabya British Schools]]|accessdate=2019-07-09}}</ref>\n* [[\u00dcsk\u00fcdar University]]\n\n==Twin towns==\n===Twin municipalities===\n*{{flagicon|NMK}} [[Municipality of Saraj (Skopje)|Saraj]], [[Skopje]]<ref>[http://ina-online.net/maqedoni/17899.html Komuna e Sarajit binjak\u00ebzim me komun\u00ebn turke Uskudar] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604001559/http://ina-online.net/maqedoni/17899.html |date=4 June 2012 }}, INA, 1 June 2012 (in Albanian)</ref>\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailysabah.com/istanbul/2015/08/12/brooklyn-uskudar-istanbul-and-new-yorks-iconic-districts-join-forces|title=Brooklyn-\u00dcsk\u00fcdar: Istanbul and New York\u2019s iconic districts join forces|website=Dailysabah.com|accessdate=16 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notable residents==\n*[[Richard Guyon]] (1813\u20131856), British-born Hungarian soldier, general in the Hungarian revolutionary army\n*[[Maximus the Confessor]] \u2013 [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] monk, theologian and scholar. He entered a monastery in Chrysopolis in the early 7th century.<ref>{{cite book |first = George Thomas |last = Kurian |title = The Encyclopedia of Christian Literature |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=dk4G-52QT-8C&pg=PA454&lpg=PA454&dq=Patriarch+pyrrhus+of+Constantinople+chrysopolis&source=bl&ots=rgtwsyNPtq&sig=6pvLlbohc3fn1tMvQcBcR4N_Svs&hl=en&ei=zRycTuPEOJCk-gaUz7WvDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CGUQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=Patriarch%20pyrrhus%20of%20Constantinople%20chrysopolis&f=false |page=454|year =2010 |publisher = Scarecrow Press |isbn = 0-8108-6987-X}}</ref>\n*[[Philippicus (general)|Philippicus]] - Byzantine general; a monk in Chrysopolis between 602\u2013610, and buried in Chrysopolis.<ref>{{cite book |first = Michael |last = Whitby |title = The Emperor Maurice and his Historian \u2013 Theophylact Simocatta on Persian and Balkan Warfare |url = https://books.google.gr/books?id=VAcAJfJP9KUC&hl=en |page=129|year = 1988 |publisher = Oxford University Press |isbn = 0-19-822945-3}}</ref>\n*[[Sergius I of Constantinople]] - Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople.<ref>{{cite book |first = Bernhard |last = Bischoff |title = Biblical commentaries from the Canterbury school of Theodore and Hadrian |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=P4kmkDO_5qcC&pg=PA65&lpg=PA65&dq=Patriarch+Pyrrhus+of+Constantinople+chrysopolis&source=bl&ots=Ra9p2bfKI-&sig=2Wu23xVMsKY_GmyYfDa_Wdk1FuE&hl=en&ei=LBqcTuDOC4OdOtuYuIkK&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=8&ved=0CFoQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=Patriarch%20Pyrrhus%20of%20Constantinople%20chrysopolis&f=false |page=59|year =1994 |publisher = Cambridge University Press |isbn = 0-521-33089-0}}</ref>\n*[[Patriarch Pyrrhus of Constantinople]] - Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople.<ref>{{cite book |first = Demetrios |last = Bathrellos |title = The Byzantine Christ: person, nature, and will in the Christology of Saint Maximus the Confessor |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=P4kmkDO_5qcC&pg=PA65&lpg=PA65&dq=Patriarch+Pyrrhus+of+Constantinople+chrysopolis&source=bl&ots=Ra9p2bfKI-&sig=2Wu23xVMsKY_GmyYfDa_Wdk1FuE&hl=en&ei=LBqcTuDOC4OdOtuYuIkK&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=8&ved=0CFoQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=Patriarch%20Pyrrhus%20of%20Constantinople%20chrysopolis&f=false |page=65|year =2004 |publisher = Oxford University Press |isbn = 0-19-925864-3}}</ref>\n*[[Alexios Mosele (Caesar)|Alexios Mosele]] - Byzantine aristocrat and general<ref>{{cite book |first = John |last = Skylitzes |title = A Synopsis of Byzantine History, 811-1057 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=P4kmkDO_5qcC&pg=PA65&lpg=PA65&dq=Patriarch+Pyrrhus+of+Constantinople+chrysopolis&source=bl&ots=Ra9p2bfKI-&sig=2Wu23xVMsKY_GmyYfDa_Wdk1FuE&hl=en&ei=LBqcTuDOC4OdOtuYuIkK&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=8&ved=0CFoQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=Patriarch%20Pyrrhus%20of%20Constantinople%20chrysopolis&f=false |page=66|year =2010 |publisher = Cambridge University Press |isbn = 0-521-76705-9}}</ref>\n*[[Michael III]] - Byzantine emperor\n*[[Florence Nightingale]] - English nurse, writer and statistician\n*[[Mehmet Akif Ersoy]] - Turkish poet of the [[Turkish national anthem]]\n*[[Halide Edip Ad\u0131var]] - Turkish novelist and feminist political leader\n*[[Xenophon Sideridis]] - Greek historian, writer and researcher\n*[[\u015eeker Ahmed Pasha]] \u2013 Turkish painter\n*[[Mehmed Orhan]] \u2013 Turkish aristocrat, a pretender to the throne of the [[Ottoman Dynasty]]\n*[[M\u00fcnir Erteg\u00fcn]] \u2013 Turkish legal counsel in international law to the Ottoman Empire and diplomat of Turkey\n*[[Ahmet Erteg\u00fcn]] \u2013 Turkish-American musician and businessman, and founder and president of [[Atlantic Records]] and [[New York Cosmos (1971\u20131985)|New York Cosmos]] soccer team\n*[[Nesuhi Erteg\u00fcn]] \u2013 Turkish-American record producer and executive of [[Atlantic Records]] and [[Warner Music Group|WEA International]]\n*[[Bar\u0131\u015f Man\u00e7o]] \u2013 Turkish rock singer, composer, and television producer\n*[[B\u00fclent Ersoy]] \u2013 transgender Turkish celebrity and singer of Ottoman classical music\n*[[\u00d6zg\u00fc Namal]] \u2013 Turkish actress\n*[[Zabel Sibil Asadour]] \u2013 [[Armenian people|Armenian]] poet and writer\n*[[Calouste Gulbenkian]] \u2013  Armenian businessman and philanthropist, once the richest man in the world\n*[[Garabet Yazmaciyan]] \u2013 Armenian painter\n*[[Onnik Chifte-Saraf]] \u2013 Armenian writer\n*[[Gabriel Noradunkyan]] \u2013 Ottoman Armenian politician\n*[[Yeghishe Tourian of Jerusalem|Yeghishe Tourian]] \u2013 Armenian Patriarch of Jerusalem and Constantinople\n*[[Bedros Tourian]] \u2013 Armenian poet\n*[[Hovhannes Hintliyan]] \u2013 Armenian pedagogue and educator\n*[[Hrand Nazariantz]] \u2013 Armenian poet and writer\n*[[Levon Shant]] \u2013 Armenian poet, writer, and playwright\n*[[Sirvart Kalpakyan Karamanuk]] \u2013 Armenian composer, pianist, and teacher\n*[[Schahan Berberian]] \u2013 Armenian philosopher, composer, and pedagogue\n*[[Srpuhi Kalfayan]] \u2013 Armenian nun and philanthropist\n*[[Zabel Yesayan]] \u2013 Armenian poet, writer, and teacher\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography ==\n*{{cite book |title=Ad\u0131m Ad\u0131m \u0130stanbul \u0130nan\u00e7 Atlas\u0131: Camiler, T\u00fcrbeler, Ziyaret Yerleri, Mezarl\u0131klar |year=2004 |publisher=Mapmedya |isbn=975-6206-02-0}}\n*{{cite book |last=H\u00fcrel|first=Haldun |title=Semtleri, Mahalleri, Caddeleri ve Sokaklar\u0131 A'dan Z'ye \u0130stanbul'un Alfabetik \u00d6yk\u00fcs\u00fc |year=2008|publisher=\u0130karus |isbn=978-975-999-290-3}}\n*{{cite book |last=Kumbarac\u0131lar |first=\u0130zzet |title=\u0130stanbul Sebilleri |year=2008 |publisher=Kap\u0131 |isbn=978-9944-486-87-3}} (First published 1938)\n*{{cite book |last=Tu\u011flac\u0131 |first=Pars |title=\u0130stanbul Ermeni Kiliseleri = Armenian Churches of Istanbul = Ist\u02bbanpuli Hayots\u02bb ekeghets\u02bbiner\u011b |year=1991 |publisher=Pars |isbn=975-7423-00-9}}\n\n{{commons category|\u00dcsk\u00fcdar}}\n\n{{\u00dcsk\u00fcdar}}\n{{Districts of Turkey |provname=Istanbul|sortkey=Uskudar}}\n{{Anatolian neighborhoods of \u0130stanbul by the Bosphorus}}\n\n{{Coord|41|01|N|29|02|E|display=title|region:TR_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Uskudar}}\n[[Category:Bosphorus]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Istanbul Province]]\n[[Category:\u00dcsk\u00fcdar| ]]\n[[Category:Districts of Istanbul Province]]\n[[Category:Transit centers in Istanbul]]\n[[Category:Megarian colonies in Thrace]]\n[[Category:Populated places of the Byzantine Empire|Chrysopolis]]\n", "name_user": "SilkTork", "label": "safe", "comment": "Erteg\u00fcn to Ertegun, replaced: Erteg\u00fcn \u2192 Ertegun (5)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%9Csk%C3%BCdar"}
{"title_page": "Huda Zoghbi", "text_new": "{{short description|Lebanese scientist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Huda Yahya Zoghbi<ref>{{cite news|author1=Cha, Ariana Eunjung|title=Silicon Valley's 'Nobels': Mega-prizes awarded for work in brains, the origins of life and gravitational waves|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/to-your-health/wp/2016/12/04/silicon-valleys-nobels-mega-prizes-awarded-for-work-in-brains-the-origins-of-life-and-gravitational-waves/?noredirect=on|accessdate=13 Dec 2018|work=[[Washington Post]]|date=4 Dec 2016}}{{dead link|date=March 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n| image = Huda Zoghbi.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = Huda El-Hibri\n| birth_date = {{birth year and age|1954}}<ref name=\"thescientist\">{{cite magazine|last=Azvolinsky|first=Anna|date=1 Nov 2018|title=Genetic Neurologist: A Profile of Huda Zoghbi|url=https://www.the-scientist.com/profile/genetic-neurologist--a-profile-of-huda-zoghbi-64943|magazine=|location=|publisher=[[The Scientist (magazine)|The Scientist]]|accessdate=13 Dec 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Beirut]], [[Lebanon]]\n| nationality = \n| fields = [[Genetics]] <br/> [[Neuroscience]]\n| workplaces = [[Regeneron Pharmaceuticals]]<ref name=\"regeneron\">{{cite web|title=Huda Y. Zoghbi, M.D.|url=https://investor.regeneron.com/board-directors/huda-zoghbi|publisher=[[Regeneron Pharmaceuticals]]|accessdate=13 Dec 2018}}</ref> <br/> [[Baylor College of Medicine]] <br/> [[Howard Hughes Medical Institute]] <br/> [[Texas Children's Hospital]]\n| alma_mater = [[Baylor College of Medicine]] <br/> [[Meharry Medical College]] <br/> [[American University of Beirut]]\n| doctoral_advisor = \n| known_for = Research in [[Rett syndrome]] and [[spinocerebellar ataxia type 1]]\n| website = \n| spouse = [[William Zoghbi]]<ref name=\"shawautobio\">{{cite web|author=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|title=Autobiography of Huda Y Zoghbi|url=http://www.shawprize.org/en/shaw.php?tmp=3&twoid=102&threeid=255&fourid=475&fiveid=233|publisher=[[Shaw Prize|Shaw Prize Foundation]]|accessdate=13 Dec 2018|date=27 Sep 2016}}</ref>\n| awards = [[Texas]] Women Hall of Fame {{small|(2008)}} <br> [[Gruber Prize in Neuroscience]] {{small|(2011)}} <br> [[Pearl Meister Greengard Prize]] {{small|(2013)}} <br> [[Dickson Prize]] {{small|(2013)}} <br> [[Shaw Prize|Shaw Prize in Life Science and Medicine]] {{small|(2016)}} <br> [[Gairdner Foundation International Award|Canada Gairdner International Award]] {{small|(2017)}} <br> [[Breakthrough Prize in Life Sciences]] {{small|(2017)}} <br> [[The Brain Prize|Brain Prize]] {{small|(2020)}}\n}}\n'''Huda Yahya Zoghbi''' ([[Arabic Language|Arabic]]:  \u0647\u062f\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0647\u0628\u0631\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0632\u063a\u0628\u064a ''Hud\u0101 al-Hibr\u012b az-Zughb\u012b''; born 1954), born Huda El-Hibri,<ref name=\"thescientist\"/> is a Lebanese-born American [[genetics|geneticist]], and a professor at the Department of [[Molecular genetics|Molecular]] and [[Human]] Genetics, [[Baylor College of Medicine]].<ref name=\"baylor\">{{cite web|title=Huda Yahya Zoghbi, M.D.|url=https://www.bcm.edu/people/view/huda-zoghbi-m-d/genetics-research-faculty-u-z/b1855108-ffed-11e2-be68-080027880ca6/53710912-91bc-42a4-9400-2d630a1612dc|publisher=[[Baylor College of Medicine]]|accessdate=13 Dec 2018}}</ref>  Her work helped elucidate mechanisms of [[Rett syndrome]] and [[spinocerebellar ataxia type 1]]. In 2017, she was awarded the [[Gairdner Foundation International Award|Canada Gairdner International Award]] and the [[Breakthrough Prize in Life Sciences]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nHuda Zoghbi was born in [[Beirut]], [[Lebanon]] in 1954, and raised in Beirut. She loved reading works by [[William Shakespeare]], [[Jane Austen]] and [[William Wordsworth]] in high school and intended to pursue [[literature]] at university<ref name=\"pnas\" />. Her mother convinced her to study [[biology]] instead, on the grounds that 'a woman growing up in the Middle East should pick a career ensuring independence and security, while she can always write on the side'.<ref name=\"jax\">{{cite news|author1=Ellen, Elliot|title=Women in science: Huda Zoghbi discovered the genetic basis of Rett syndrome|url=https://www.jax.org/news-and-insights/jax-blog/2018/march/women-in-science-huda-zoghbi-autism|accessdate=13 Dec 2018|publisher=[[Jackson Laboratory]]|date=12 Mar 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"pnas\">{{cite journal|author1=Nuzzo, Regina|title=Profile of Huda Y. Zoghbi|journal=[[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America]]|date=28 Feb 2006|volume=103|issue=9|pages=3017\u20133019|doi=10.1073/pnas.0509604103|pmid=16492741|pmc=1413894}}</ref>  Zoghbi was admitted as a [[biological sciences]] major at the [[American University of Beirut]] (AUB) in 1973 and entered the university's [[medical school]] 2 years later.<ref name=pnas/>\n\nThe [[Lebanese Civil War]] began in 1976 during her first year of medical school.  Although she and her classmates decided to stay at the university, after her brother was injured by shrapnel, their parents sent them to live with their sister in [[Austin]], [[Texas]], with plans to return the following summer.<ref name=\"pnas\"/><ref name=\"jci\">{{cite journal|author1=Neill, Ushma S.|title=A conversation with Huda Zoghbi|journal=[[Journal of Clinical Investigation]]|date=1 Mar 2016|volume=126|issue=3|pages=797\u2013798|doi=10.1172/JCI86445|pmid=26928032|pmc=4767342}}</ref> The war, however, raged on, and Zoghbi was under the impression that school terms at American medical schools began in October, as was the case with Lebanese schools. However, in October, it was confirmed that she was still unable to return to Lebanon due to the war, and US medical schools had begun their fall term 2 months earlier. Her family friends in America suggested she apply to [[Vanderbilt University]].  Vanderbilt did not accept transfer students, but recommended [[Meharry Medical College]] instead; Meharry accepted her on the spot.<ref name=\"jci\"/> Despite her continued desire to return to Lebanon the next summer, on the advice of professors at AUB, she stayed at Meharry and earned an [[Doctor of Medicine|MD]] degree in 1979, after which she joined the [[Texas Children's Hospital]] at the [[Baylor College of Medicine]] as a [[pediatrics|pediatric]] resident.<ref name=\"pnas\"/>\n\nZoghbi initially intended to specialise in pediatric [[cardiology]], out of an interest in the heart. During her rotation at pediatric [[neurology]], Marvin Fishman, the head of the division, convinced her that the [[brain]] was more interesting than the heart. She thus started a 3-year term as a [[postdoctoral researcher]] in pediatric neurology after she finished her residency in 1982.\n\n== Career ==\nFrom 1982 to 1985, Zoghbi was a [[postdoctoral researcher]] in pediatric neurology at the [[Baylor College of Medicine]]. She became an assistant professor at the Department of Pediatrics at Baylor in 1988, and was successively promoted to associate professor in 1991 and professor in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|title=Biographical Notes of Laureates|url=http://www.shawprize.org/en/shaw.php?tmp=3&twoid=102&threeid=255&fourid=472|publisher=[[Shaw Prize|Shaw Prize Foundation]]|accessdate=13 Dec 2018|date=31 May 2016}}</ref> At present, Zoghbi is a professor at the Department of [[Molecular genetics|Molecular]] and [[Human]] Genetics at Baylor, with appointments as a professor at the Department of [[Neuroscience]] and the Department of [[Pediatrics]] Section of Neurology and Developmental Neuroscience, the [[Ralph Feigin|Ralph Feigin, M.D.]] Endowed Chair, the director of the [[Texas Children's Hospital]] Jan and Dan Duncan Neurological Research Institute, a member of the Dan L. Duncan Comprehensive Cancer Center at Baylor, and an investigator at the [[Howard Hughes Medical Institute]].<ref name=\"baylor\"/> She is also a member of the board of directors of [[Regeneron Pharmaceuticals]].<ref name=\"regeneron\"/>\n\n== Research ==\nIn 1983, Zoghbi learnt of [[Rett syndrome]] from Bengt Hagberg's account in ''[[Annals of Neurology]]''. The paper allowed Zoghbi to diagnose a five-year-old she treated at [[Texas Children's Hospital]], and a week later she saw another patient with the same set of symptoms. When she investigated medical records, she found more cases of Rett syndrome that had been misdiagnosed. This sparked her interest in Rett syndrome, at a time when there was no report of the disease in the US.<ref name=\"thescientist\"/> An article she published in 1985<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|author2=Percy, Alan K.|author3=Glaze, Daniel G.|author4=Butler, Ian J.|author5=Riccardi, Vincent M.|title=Reduction of Biogenic Amine Levels in the Rett Syndrome|journal=[[New England Journal of Medicine]]|date=10 Oct 1985|volume=33|issue=15|pages=921\u2013924|doi=10.1056/NEJM198510103131504|pmid=2412119}}</ref> attracted many Rett syndrome patients to Texas Children's Hospital, giving her access to a large number of cases.<ref name=\"interview\">{{cite interview|last=Zoghbi|first=Huda|subject-link=Huda Zoghbi|interviewer=McMullen Darra|title=Interview with Huda Zoghbi|url=https://digitalcommons.library.tmc.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1017&context=tmc-whp|publisher=[[Texas Medical Center]] Women's History Project|location=|date=9 Feb 2016|work=|access-date=13 Dec 2018}}</ref>\n\nSince most patients of Rett syndrome were girls, and symptoms were very consistent across patients, Zoghbi believed [[genetics]] were involved in the disease process.<ref name=\"thescientist\" /> This led her to join [[Arthur Beaudet]]'s group in 1985, after finishing her term as a [[postdoctoral researcher]], for training in genetics and [[molecular biology]].<ref name=\"jci\"/> Beaudet advised against Rett syndrome as her research project since its mode of inheritance was still not obvious, and recommended a more approachable problem - [[spinocerebellar ataxia type 1]], a [[dominance (genetics)|dominantly]] inherited neurological disorder. In 1988, Zoghbi left Beaudet's group and founded her own lab at Baylor.<ref name=\"pnas\"/> In addition to her research on spinocerebellar ataxia type 1 and Rett syndrome, Zoghbi is participating in a joint research collaboration into [[CDKL5]] Deficiency Disorder, funded by the Loulou Foundation, Baylor College of Medicine and the Jan and Dan Duncan Neurological Research Institute (NRI) at [[Texas Children's Hospital|Texas Children\u2019s Hospital]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bcm.edu/news/research/research-focuses-on-cdkl5-deficiency|title=Research collaboration focuses on CDKL5 Deficiency Disorder|last=Gutierrez|first=Graciela|date=Oct 30, 2019|website=Baylor College of Medicine Research News|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Spinocerebellar ataxia type 1 ===\nFollowing the establishment of her own lab, Zoghbi continued studying [[spinocerebellar ataxia type 1]] (SCA1), in collaboration with Harry Orr from the [[University of Minnesota]]. On the same day, 8 April 1993, both Zoghbi and Orr identified [[Ataxin 1|ATXN1]] as the gene responsible for SCA1.<ref name=\"jci\"/> They determined that the disease was caused by an [[trinucleotide repeat expansion|expansion]] of the [[glutamine]]-encoding CAG trinucleotide repeat in this gene, and that the younger the age of onset, the longer the CAG repeat.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Orr, Harry T.|author2=Chung, Ming-yi|author3=Banfi, Sandro|author4=Kwiatkowski Jr., Thomas J.|author5=Servadio, Antonio|author6=Beaudet, Arthur L.|author7=McCall, Alanna E.|author8=Duvick, Lisa A.|author9=Ranum, Laura P. W.|author10=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|title=Expansion of an unstable trinucleotide CAG repeat in spinocerebellar ataxia type 1|journal=[[Nature Genetics]]|date=1 Jul 1993|volume=4|issue=3|pages=221\u2013226|doi=10.1038/ng0793-221|pmid=8358429}}</ref>  Further work by Zoghbi, Orr and their teams demonstrated that the [[protein folding|misfolding]], aggregation, and [[proteasome|proteasomal]] [[proteolysis|degradation]] of the [[protein]] product of this gene, [[Ataxin 1]], played a role in the disorder.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Cummings, Christopher J.|author2=Mancini, Michael A.|author3=Antalffy, Barbara|author4=DeFranco, Donald B.|author5=Orr, Harry T.|author6=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|title=Chaperone suppression of aggregation and altered subcellular proteasome localization imply protein misfolding in SCA1|journal=Nature Genetics|date=1 Jun 1998|volume=19|issue=2|pages=148\u2013154|doi=10.1038/502|pmid=9620770}}</ref>\n\n=== Math1 ===\nAfter solving the [[etiology]] of [[spinocerebellar ataxia type 1]], Zoghbi began studying animal genes related to [[balance (ability)|balance]]. As Baylor's [[Hugo J. Bellen]] described the role of the ''atonal'' gene in balance in [[Drosophila melanogaster|fruit flies]], Zoghbi chose to study its [[mammal]]ian [[sequence homology|homolog]].  A member of her lab successfully cloned the mouse homolog, ''[[ATOH1|Math1]]'', in 1996.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Ben-Arie, Nissim|author2=McCall, Alanna E.|author3=Berkman, Scott|author4=Eichele, Gregor|author5=Bellen, Hugo J.|author6=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|title=Evolutionary conservation of sequence and expression of the bHLH protein Atonal suggests a conserved role in neurogenesis|journal=[[Human Molecular Genetics]]|date=1 Sep 1996|volume=5|issue=9|pages=1207\u20131216|doi=10.1093/hmg/5.9.1207|pmid=8872459|doi-access=free}}</ref> Her team went on to find that, in addition to its involvement in balance and coordination, ''Math1'' is also crucial to hearing <ref>{{cite journal|author1=Bermingham, Nessan A.|author2=Hassan, Bassem A.|author3=Price, Steven D.|author4=Vollrath, Melissa A.|author5=Ben-Arie, Nissim|author6=Eatock, Ruth A.|author7=Bellen, Hugo J.|author8=Lysakowski, Anna|author9=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|title=Math1: An Essential Gene for the Generation of Inner Ear Hair Cells|journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]]|date=11 Jun 1999|volume=284|issue=5421|pages=1837\u20131841|doi=10.1126/science.284.5421.1837|pmid=10364557}}</ref> and the formation of secretory cells in the gut.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Yang, Qi|author2=Bermingham, Nessan A.|author3=Finegold, Milton J.|author4=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|title=Requirement of Math1 for secretory cell lineage commitment in the mouse intestine|journal=Science|date=7 Dec 2001|volume=294|issue=5549|pages=2155\u20132158|doi=10.1126/science.1065718|pmid=11739954}}</ref> Her lab has also shown that aberrant activation of ''Math1'' could lead to [[medulloblastoma]], a common childhood brain tumor, and that mice which did not express ''Math1,'' did not develop the tumor.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Flora|first1=Adriano|last2=Klisch|first2=Tiemo J.|last3=Schuster|first3=Gabriele|last4=Zoghbi|first4=Huda Y.|title=Deletion of Atoh1 Disrupts Sonic Hedgehog Signaling in the Developing Cerebellum and Prevents Medulloblastoma|journal=Science|date=4 Dec 2009|volume=326|issue=5958|pages=1424\u20131427|doi=10.1126/science.1181453|pmid=19965762|pmc=3638077}}</ref>\n\n===Rett syndrome===\n\nEver since Zoghbi was introduced to [[Rett syndrome]] early in her career, she has been working on the disorder alongside other research, despite the lack of enthusiasm from her colleagues, fellow researchers and funding agencies. The main reason is that very few individuals and even fewer families are available for investigation. In the 1990s, she collaborated with [[Uta Francke]] from [[Stanford University]] to identify the gene responsible for Rett syndrome. In 1992, she narrowed down the target to a section of the [[X chromosome]].<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Ellison, Kimberley A.|author2=Fill, Carolyn P.|author3=Terwilliger, Joseph|author4=DeGennaro, Louis J.|author5=Martin-Gallardo, Antonia|author6=Anvret, Maria|author7=Percy, Alan K.|author8=Ott, Jurg|author9=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|title=Examination of X chromosome markers in Rett syndrome: exclusion mapping with a novel variation on multilocus linkage analysis|journal=[[American Journal of Human Genetics]]|date=Feb 1992|volume=50|issue=2|pages=278\u2013287|pmid=1734712|pmc=1682446}}</ref> In 1999, a [[postdoctoral researcher]] in Zoghbi's lab identified [[MECP2]] as the causative gene.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Amir, Ruthie E.|author2=Van den Veyver, Ignatia B.|author3=Wan, Mimi|author4=Tran, Charles Q.|author5=Francke, Uta|author6=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|title=Rett syndrome is caused by mutations in X-linked MECP2, encoding methyl-CpG-binding protein 2|journal=Nature Genetics|date=1 Oct 1999|volume=23|issue=2|pages=185\u2013188|doi=10.1038/13810|pmid=10508514}}</ref> The MECP2 [[protein]] binds [[DNA methylation|methylated]] [[cytosine]] ([[5-methylcytosine]]) in [[CpG sites]], and is indispensable for almost all [[brain cells]].<ref name=\"jci\"/> In the paper, she and her team demonstrated that Rett syndrome was an [[X-linked dominant inheritance|X-linked dominant]] disorder, meaning that when 1 of the 2 copies of the MECP2 gene is abnormal, Rett syndrome will result.<ref name=\"jax\"/>\n\nZoghbi's team keeps studying MECP2, and discovered in 2004 that overexpressing the protein in mouse led to an [[autism]]-like neurological disorder.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Collins, Ann L.|author2=Levenson, Jonathan M.|author3=Vilaythong, Alexander P.|author4=Richman, Ronald|author5=Armstrong, Dawna L.|author6=Noebels, Jeffrey L.|author7=Sweatt, J. David|author8=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|title=Mild overexpression of MeCP2 causes a progressive neurological disorder in mice|journal=Human Molecular Genetics|date=6 Sep 2004|volume=13|issue=21|pages=2679\u20132689|doi=10.1093/hmg/ddh282|pmid=15351775|doi-access=free}}</ref> In 2009, she found mice deficient of the Mecp2 gene (the mouse homolog of human MECP2) had lower levels of [[norepinephrine]], [[dopamine]] and [[serotonin]],<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Samaco, Rodney C.|author2=Mandel-Brehm, Caleigh|author3=Chao, Hsiao-Tuan|author4=Ward, Christopher S.|author5=Fyffe-Maricich, Sharyl L.|author6=Ren, Jun|author7=Hyland, Keith |author8=Thaller, Christina |author9=Maricich, Stephen M.|author10=Humphreys, Peter |author11=Greer, John J.|author12=Percy, Alan|author13=Glaze, Daniel G.|author14=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|author15=Neul, Jeffrey L.|title=Loss of MeCP2 in aminergic neurons causes cell-autonomous defects in neurotransmitter synthesis and specific behavioral abnormalities|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|date=22 Dec 2009|volume=106|issue=51|pages=21966\u201321971|doi=10.1073/pnas.0912257106|pmid=20007372|pmc=2799790}}</ref> consistent with her clinical observations of patients of Rett syndrome in 1985. Recently, Zoghbi confirmed that the MECP2 protein also bound 5-methylcytosine not in CpG sites,<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Chen, Lin|author2=Chen, Kaifu|author3=Lavery, Laura A.|author4=Baker, Steven A.|author5=Shaw, Chad A.|author6=Li, Wei|author7=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|title=MeCP2 binds to non-CG methylated DNA as neurons mature, influencing transcription and the timing of onset for Rett syndrome|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|date=28 Apr 2015|volume=112|issue=17|pages=5509\u20135514|doi=10.1073/pnas.1505909112|pmid=25870282|pmc=4418849}}</ref> and that restoring the level of MECP2 protein in a subset of [[neurons]] was sufficient to rescue some symptoms of Rett syndrome.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Ure, Kerstin|author2=Lu, Hui|author3=Wang, Wei|author4=Ito-Ishida, Aya|author5=Wu, Zhenyu|author6=He, Ling-jie|author7=Sztainberg, Yehezkel|author8=Chen, Wu|author9=Tang, Jianrong|author10=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|title=Restoration of Mecp2 expression in GABAergic neurons is sufficient to rescue multiple disease features in a mouse model of Rett syndrome|journal=[[eLife]]|date=21 Jun 2016|volume=5|pages=e14198|doi=10.7554/eLife.14198|pmid=27328321|pmc=4946897}}</ref>\n\n=== Ataxin-1 link to Alzheimer's ===\nAfter linking the gene Ataxin-1 to SCA1, Zoghbi's lab was approached by Dr. Jaehong Suh of the [[Massachusetts General Hospital|Massachusetts General Hospita]]<nowiki/>l's MassGeneral Institute for Neurodegenerative Disease to investigate the connection between ataxin-1 gene and [[Alzheimer's disease|Alzheimer\u2019s disease]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.bcm.edu/2019/09/05/from-the-labs-ataxin-1-one-gene-two-different-neurodegenerative-diseases/|title=Ataxin-1: One gene, two different neurodegenerative diseases|last=Rodr\u00edguez|first=Ana Mar\u00eda|date=September 5, 2019|website=Baylor College of Medicine, From the Labs|access-date=}}</ref> The subsequent study found that loss of ataxin-1 elevates BACE1 expression and A\u03b2 pathology in mouse models, rendering it a potential contributor to risk and pathogenesis of Alzheimer's disease.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Suh|first=Jaehong|date=22 August 2019|title=Loss of Ataxin-1 Potentiates Alzheimer\u2019s Pathogenesis by Elevating Cerebral BACE1 Transcription|url=https://www.cell.com/cell/fulltext/S0092-8674(19)30843-8|journal=Cell|volume=Volume 178, Issue 5|pages=1159-1175.e17|via=Elsevier Science Direct}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n* 2020 - [[The Brain Prize|Brain Prize]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lundbeckfonden.com/en/thebrainprize/winners/|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n* 2019 - Victor A. McKusick Leadership Award, [[American Society of Human Genetics]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ashg.org/awards/awards_2019winners.shtml|title=2019 ASHG Award Recipients {{!}} ASHG|website=www.ashg.org|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref>\n* 2018 - Member of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] <ref>{{cite web|title=Dr. Huda Y. Zoghbi|url=https://www.amacad.org/content/system/search.aspx?t=50&s=zoghbi|publisher=[[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]|accessdate=14 Dec 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206001545/https://www.amacad.org/content/system/search.aspx?t=50&s=zoghbi|archive-date=6 December 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* 2018 - Ross Prize in Molecular Medicine, [[Molecular Medicine (journal)|Molecular Medicine]] <ref>{{cite press release|last=|first=|date=8 Mar 2018|title=Molecular Medicine awards Ross Prize to Baylor College of Medicine's Huda Zoghbi|url=https://www.feinsteininstitute.org/2018/03/molecular-medicine-awards-ross-prize-to-baylor-college-of-medicines-huda-zoghbi/|location=|publisher=[[Feinstein Institute for Medical Research]]|agency=|access-date=14 Dec 2018}}</ref>\n* 2018 - [[National Order of the Cedar]], [[Lebanon]] <ref>{{cite news|title=Dr. Huda Zoghbi receives Lebanon's highest honor|url=https://nri.texaschildrens.org/news/dr-huda-zoghbi-receives-lebanons-highest-honor|accessdate=14 Dec 2018|publisher=Jan and Dan Duncan Neurological Research Institute|date=23 Jan 2018}}</ref>\n* 2017 - [[Breakthrough Prize in Life Sciences]] <ref>{{cite web|title=Breakthrough Prize Life Sciences Laureates 2017|url=https://breakthroughprize.org/Laureates/2/P1/Y2017|publisher=[[Breakthrough Prize|Break Prize Foundation]]|accessdate=14 Dec 2018}}</ref>\n* 2017 - [[Gairdner Foundation International Award|Canada Gairdner International Award]] <ref>{{cite web|title=Huda Y Zoghbi|url=https://gairdner.org/winners/index-of-winners/?_sfm_winner_type=Canada%20Gairdner%20International%20Award&_sfm_winner_year=1959+2020#Huda_Y_Zoghbi|publisher=[[Gairdner Foundation International Award|Gairdner Foundation]]|accessdate=14 Dec 2018}}</ref>\n* 2016 - [[Jessie Stevenson Kovalenko Medal]] <ref>{{cite web|title=Jessie Stevenson Kovalenko Medal|url=http://www.nasonline.org/programs/awards/kovalenko-medal.html|publisher=[[National Academy of Sciences]]|accessdate=14 Dec 2018}}</ref>\n* 2016 - [[Shaw Prize|Shaw Prize in Life Science and Medicine]]\n* 2015 - Mechthild Esser Nemmers Prize in [[Medical Science]], [[Northwestern University]]\n* 2015 - Vanderbilt Prize in Biomedical Science, [[Vanderbilt University School of Medicine]]\n* 2015 - Javits [[Neuroscience]] Investigator Award, [[National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke]] (NINDS), [[National Institutes of Health]]\n* 2015 - American Task Force for Lebanon Award\n* 2015 - [[Mortimer Sackler|Mortimer D. Sackler, M.D.]] Prize for Distinguished Achievement in [[Developmental Psychobiology]], [[Weill Cornell Medicine]] and [[Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons]] <ref name=\"viictr\">{{cite web|title=Huda Yahya Zoghbi|url=https://profiles.viictr.org/display/267945|publisher=Virtually Integrated Institutions for Clinical and Translational Research|accessdate=14 Dec 2018}}</ref>\n* 2014 - Honorary Doctor of Medical Sciences, [[Yale University]] <ref>{{cite news|title=Yale awards 12 honorary degrees at 2014 graduation|url=https://news.yale.edu/2014/05/19/yale-awards-12-honorary-degrees-2014-graduation|accessdate=14 Dec 2018|publisher=[[Yale University]]|date=19 May 2014}}</ref>\n* 2014 - [[March of Dimes]] Prize in [[Developmental Biology]]\n* 2014 - Edward M. Scolnick Prize in Neuroscience, [[McGovern Institute for Brain Research]], [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] <ref>{{cite news|last1=Jennings|first1=Charles|title=McGovern Institute to honor neurogenetics researcher Huda Zoghbi|url=http://mcgovern.mit.edu/news/news/mcgovern-institute-to-honor-neurogenetics-researcher-huda-zoghbi/|accessdate=14 Dec 2018|publisher=[[McGovern Institute for Brain Research]]|date=4 Mar 2014}}</ref>\n* 2013 - [[Dickson Prize|Dickson Prize in Medicine]], [[University of Pittsburgh]]\n* 2013 - [[Pearl Meister Greengard Prize]], [[Rockefeller University]]\n* 2011 - [[Gruber Prize in Neuroscience]] <ref name=\"baylor\"/>\n* 2011 - Vita and Lee Lyman Dewey Tuttle Brookwood Legacy Award for Excellence and Partnership in Medicine, Brookwood Community <ref>{{cite news|title=Texas Children's Hospital Neuroscientist Dr. Huda Zoghbi Receives 2011 Legacy Award from The Brookwood Community|url=https://www.texaschildrens.org/about-us/news/releases/texas-childrens-hospital-neuroscientist-dr-huda-zoghbi-receives-2011-legacy|accessdate=14 Dec 2018|publisher=[[Texas Children's Hospital]]}}</ref>\n* 2009 - International [[Rett Syndrome]] Foundation's Circle of Angels Research Award \n* 2009 - Vilcek Prize for Biomedical Research, [[The Vilcek Foundation|Vilcek Foundation]]\n* 2009 - Marion Spencer Fay Award, [[Drexel University College of Medicine]] <ref name=\"baylor\"/>\n* 2009 - Cathedra Laboris, [[University of Monterrey]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.udem.edu.mx/Eng/VIAC/Pages/DICSA/catedra-laboris.aspx|title=Cathedra Laboris|publisher=[[University of Monterrey]]|access-date=September 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913045210/http://www.udem.edu.mx/Eng/VIAC/Pages/DICSA/catedra-laboris.aspx|archive-date=September 13, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* 2008 - Honorary Doctor of Science, [[Meharry Medical College]]\n* 2008 - [[Texas Women's Hall of Fame]] <ref name=\"baylor\"/>\n* 2007 - [[Perl-UNC Prize|Perl-UNC Neuroscience Prize]] <ref>{{cite news|title=Baylor College scientist wins Perl-UNC Neuroscience Prize|url=http://www.med.unc.edu/www/newsarchive/2008/may/baylor-college-scientist-wins-perl-unc-neuroscience-prize|accessdate=14 Dec 2018|publisher=[[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]]|date=20 May 2008}}</ref>\n* 2007 - Massachusetts Institute of Technology Arab Students' Organization [[Science]] and [[Technology]] Lifetime Achievement Award <ref>{{cite news|title=Arab Students' Organization hosts awards|url=https://news.mit.edu/2007/arab-sci-tech|accessdate=3 Dec 2018|publisher=[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]|date=12 Apr 2007}}</ref>\n* 2007 - Honorary Doctor of Science, [[Middlebury College]]\n* 2007 - [[Robert J. and Claire Pasarow Foundation Medical Research Award|Robert J. and Claire Pasarow Foundation Award in Neuropsychiatry Research]]\n* 2004 - Member of the [[National Academy of Sciences]]\n* 2004 - Neuronal Plasticity Prize, [[Ipsen|Ipsen Foundation]]\n* 2004 - Marta Philipson Award in Pediatrics, Philipson Foundation for Research <ref name=\"baylor\"/>\n* 2002 - Fellow of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]]\n* 2002 - Raymond D. Adams Lectureship, [[American Neurological Association]] <ref name=\"viictr\"/>\n* 2001 - [[Bernard Sachs]] Award, Society for Pediatric Research\n* 2000 - Member of the [[National Academy of Medicine]] (formerly the Institute of Medicine)\n* 1998 - Sidney Carter Award, [[American Academy of Neurology]]\n* 1998 - Soriano Lectureship, [[American Neurological Association]]\n* 1998 - Javits Award, [[NINDS]], National Institutes of Health\n* 1996 - [[E. Mead Johnson Award]], Society of Pediatric Research\n* 1995 - Kilby International Award <ref name=\"baylor\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nZoghbi met her husband, [[William Zoghbi]] when they were medical students in the [[American University of Beirut]]. In 1977, she continued her medical school study in [[Meharry Medical College]], and William transferred to Meharry next year. They both had their residencies in the [[Baylor College of Medicine]] after graduation. They married in 1980 and have 2 children.<ref name=\"shawautobio\"/> William is the chief of the Department of [[Cardiology]] at [[Houston Methodist Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web|title=William A. Zoghbi, MD, FASE, FAHA, MACC|url=https://www.houstonmethodist.org/faculty/william-zoghbi/|publisher=[[Houston Methodist Hospital]]|accessdate=14 Dec 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Scholia|author}}\n*{{Charlie Rose view|15433}}\n*{{Worldcat id|lccn-n93-802498}}\n\n{{Shaw Prize laureates}}\n{{Texas Women's Hall of Fame}}\n{{Breakthrough Prize laureates}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zoghbi, Huda}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Howard Hughes Medical Investigators]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Academy of Medicine]]\n[[Category:Baylor College of Medicine faculty]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:American neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:Lebanese pediatricians]]\n[[Category:Lebanese neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:Lebanese women neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:Lebanese women scientists]]\n[[Category:People from Beirut]]\n[[Category:American women neuroscientists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Lebanese scientist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Huda Yahya Zoghbi<ref>{{cite news|author1=Cha, Ariana Eunjung|title=Silicon Valley's 'Nobels': Mega-prizes awarded for work in brains, the origins of life and gravitational waves|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/to-your-health/wp/2016/12/04/silicon-valleys-nobels-mega-prizes-awarded-for-work-in-brains-the-origins-of-life-and-gravitational-waves/?noredirect=on|accessdate=13 Dec 2018|work=[[Washington Post]]|date=4 Dec 2016}}{{dead link|date=March 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n| image = Huda Zoghbi.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = Huda El-Hibri\n| birth_date = {{birth year and age|1954}}<ref name=\"thescientist\">{{cite magazine|last=Azvolinsky|first=Anna|date=1 Nov 2018|title=Genetic Neurologist: A Profile of Huda Zoghbi|url=https://www.the-scientist.com/profile/genetic-neurologist--a-profile-of-huda-zoghbi-64943|magazine=|location=|publisher=[[The Scientist (magazine)|The Scientist]]|accessdate=13 Dec 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Beirut]], [[Lebanon]]\n| nationality = \n| fields = [[Genetics]] <br/> [[Neuroscience]]\n| workplaces = [[Regeneron Pharmaceuticals]]<ref name=\"regeneron\">{{cite web|title=Huda Y. Zoghbi, M.D.|url=https://investor.regeneron.com/board-directors/huda-zoghbi|publisher=[[Regeneron Pharmaceuticals]]|accessdate=13 Dec 2018}}</ref> <br/> [[Baylor College of Medicine]] <br/> [[Howard Hughes Medical Institute]] <br/> [[Texas Children's Hospital]]\n| alma_mater = [[Baylor College of Medicine]] <br/> [[Meharry Medical College]] <br/> [[American University of Beirut]]\n| doctoral_advisor = \n| known_for = Research in [[Rett syndrome]] and [[spinocerebellar ataxia type 1]]\n| website = \n| spouse = [[William Zoghbi]]<ref name=\"shawautobio\">{{cite web|author=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|title=Autobiography of Huda Y Zoghbi|url=http://www.shawprize.org/en/shaw.php?tmp=3&twoid=102&threeid=255&fourid=475&fiveid=233|publisher=[[Shaw Prize|Shaw Prize Foundation]]|accessdate=13 Dec 2018|date=27 Sep 2016}}</ref>\n| awards = [[Texas]] Women Hall of Fame {{small|(2008)}} <br> [[Gruber Prize in Neuroscience]] {{small|(2011)}} <br> [[Pearl Meister Greengard Prize]] {{small|(2013)}} <br> [[Dickson Prize]] {{small|(2013)}} <br> [[Shaw Prize|Shaw Prize in Life Science and Medicine]] {{small|(2016)}} <br> [[Gairdner Foundation International Award|Canada Gairdner International Award]] {{small|(2017)}} <br> [[Breakthrough Prize in Life Sciences]] {{small|(2017)}} <br> [[The Brain Prize|Brain Prize]] {{small|(2020)}}\n}}\n'''Huda Yahya Zoghbi''' ([[Arabic Language|Arabic]]:  \u0647\u062f\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0647\u0628\u0631\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0632\u063a\u0628\u064a ''Hud\u0101 al-Hibr\u012b az-Zughb\u012b''; born 1954), born Huda El-Hibri,<ref name=\"thescientist\"/> is a Lebanese-born American [[genetics|geneticist]], and a professor at the Department of [[Molecular genetics|Molecular]] and [[Human]] Genetics, [[Baylor College of Medicine]].<ref name=\"baylor\">{{cite web|title=Huda Yahya Zoghbi, M.D.|url=https://www.bcm.edu/people/view/huda-zoghbi-m-d/genetics-research-faculty-u-z/b1855108-ffed-11e2-be68-080027880ca6/53710912-91bc-42a4-9400-2d630a1612dc|publisher=[[Baylor College of Medicine]]|accessdate=13 Dec 2018}}</ref>  Her work helped elucidate mechanisms of [[Rett syndrome]] and [[spinocerebellar ataxia type 1]]. In 2017, she was awarded the [[Gairdner Foundation International Award|Canada Gairdner International Award]] and the [[Breakthrough Prize in Life Sciences]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nHuda Zoghbi was born in [[Beirut]], [[Lebanon]] in 1954, and raised in Beirut. She loved reading works by [[William Shakespeare]], [[Jane Austen]] and [[William Wordsworth]] in high school and intended to pursue [[literature]] at university<ref name=\"pnas\" />. Her mother convinced her to study [[biology]] instead, on the grounds that 'a woman growing up in the Middle East should pick a career ensuring independence and security, while she can always write on the side'.<ref name=\"jax\">{{cite news|author1=Ellen, Elliot|title=Women in science: Huda Zoghbi discovered the genetic basis of Rett syndrome|url=https://www.jax.org/news-and-insights/jax-blog/2018/march/women-in-science-huda-zoghbi-autism|accessdate=13 Dec 2018|publisher=[[Jackson Laboratory]]|date=12 Mar 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"pnas\">{{cite journal|author1=Nuzzo, Regina|title=Profile of Huda Y. Zoghbi|journal=[[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America]]|date=28 Feb 2006|volume=103|issue=9|pages=3017\u20133019|doi=10.1073/pnas.0509604103|pmid=16492741|pmc=1413894}}</ref>  Zoghbi was admitted as a [[biological sciences]] major at the [[American University of Beirut]] (AUB) in 1973 and entered the university's [[medical school]] 2 years later.<ref name=pnas/>\n\nThe [[Lebanese Civil War]] began in 1976 during her first year of medical school.  Although she and her classmates decided to stay at the university, after her brother was injured by shrapnel, their parents sent them to live with their sister in [[Austin]], [[Texas]], with plans to return the following summer.<ref name=\"pnas\"/><ref name=\"jci\">{{cite journal|author1=Neill, Ushma S.|title=A conversation with Huda Zoghbi|journal=[[Journal of Clinical Investigation]]|date=1 Mar 2016|volume=126|issue=3|pages=797\u2013798|doi=10.1172/JCI86445|pmid=26928032|pmc=4767342}}</ref> The war, however, raged on, and Zoghbi was under the impression that school terms at American medical schools began in October, as was the case with Lebanese schools. However, in October, it was confirmed that she was still unable to return to Lebanon due to the war, and US medical schools had begun their fall term 2 months earlier. Her family friends in America suggested she apply to [[Vanderbilt University]].  Vanderbilt did not accept transfer students, but recommended [[Meharry Medical College]] instead; Meharry accepted her on the spot.<ref name=\"jci\"/> Despite her continued desire to return to Lebanon the next summer, on the advice of professors at AUB, she stayed at Meharry and earned an [[Doctor of Medicine|MD]] degree in 1979, after which she joined the [[Texas Children's Hospital]] at the [[Baylor College of Medicine]] as a [[pediatrics|pediatric]] resident.<ref name=\"pnas\"/>\n\nZoghbi initially intended to specialise in pediatric [[cardiology]], out of an interest in the heart. During her rotation at pediatric [[neurology]], Marvin Fishman, the head of the division, convinced her that the [[brain]] was more interesting than the heart. She thus started a 3-year term as a [[postdoctoral researcher]] in pediatric neurology after she finished her residency in 1982.\n\n== Career ==\nFrom 1982 to 1985, Zoghbi was a [[postdoctoral researcher]] in pediatric neurology at the [[Baylor College of Medicine]]. She became an assistant professor at the Department of Pediatrics at Baylor in 1988, and was successively promoted to associate professor in 1991 and professor in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|title=Biographical Notes of Laureates|url=http://www.shawprize.org/en/shaw.php?tmp=3&twoid=102&threeid=255&fourid=472|publisher=[[Shaw Prize|Shaw Prize Foundation]]|accessdate=13 Dec 2018|date=31 May 2016}}</ref> At present, Zoghbi is a professor at the Department of [[Molecular genetics|Molecular]] and [[Human]] Genetics at Baylor, with appointments as a professor at the Department of [[Neuroscience]] and the Department of [[Pediatrics]] Section of Neurology and Developmental Neuroscience, the [[Ralph Feigin|Ralph Feigin, M.D.]] Endowed Chair, the director of the [[Texas Children's Hospital]] Jan and Dan Duncan Neurological Research Institute, a member of the Dan L. Duncan Comprehensive Cancer Center at Baylor, and an investigator at the [[Howard Hughes Medical Institute]].<ref name=\"baylor\"/> She is also a member of the board of directors of [[Regeneron Pharmaceuticals]].<ref name=\"regeneron\"/>\n\n== Research ==\nIn 1983, Zoghbi learnt of [[Rett syndrome]] from Bengt Hagberg's account in ''[[Annals of Neurology]]''. The paper allowed Zoghbi to diagnose a five-year-old she treated at [[Texas Children's Hospital]], and a week later she saw another patient with the same set of symptoms. When she investigated medical records, she found more cases of Rett syndrome that had been misdiagnosed. This sparked her interest in Rett syndrome, at a time when there was no report of the disease in the US.<ref name=\"thescientist\"/> An article she published in 1985<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|author2=Percy, Alan K.|author3=Glaze, Daniel G.|author4=Butler, Ian J.|author5=Riccardi, Vincent M.|title=Reduction of Biogenic Amine Levels in the Rett Syndrome|journal=[[New England Journal of Medicine]]|date=10 Oct 1985|volume=33|issue=15|pages=921\u2013924|doi=10.1056/NEJM198510103131504|pmid=2412119}}</ref> attracted many Rett syndrome patients to Texas Children's Hospital, giving her access to a large number of cases.<ref name=\"interview\">{{cite interview|last=Zoghbi|first=Huda|subject-link=Huda Zoghbi|interviewer=McMullen Darra|title=Interview with Huda Zoghbi|url=https://digitalcommons.library.tmc.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1017&context=tmc-whp|publisher=[[Texas Medical Center]] Women's History Project|location=|date=9 Feb 2016|work=|access-date=13 Dec 2018}}</ref>\n\nSince most patients of Rett syndrome were girls, and symptoms were very consistent across patients, Zoghbi believed [[genetics]] were involved in the disease process.<ref name=\"thescientist\" /> This led her to join [[Arthur Beaudet]]'s group in 1985, after finishing her term as a [[postdoctoral researcher]], for training in genetics and [[molecular biology]].<ref name=\"jci\"/> Beaudet advised against Rett syndrome as her research project since its mode of inheritance was still not obvious, and recommended a more approachable problem - [[spinocerebellar ataxia type 1]], a [[dominance (genetics)|dominantly]] inherited neurological disorder. In 1988, Zoghbi left Beaudet's group and founded her own lab at Baylor.<ref name=\"pnas\"/> In addition to her research on spinocerebellar ataxia type 1 and Rett syndrome, Zoghbi is participating in a joint research collaboration into [[CDKL5]] Deficiency Disorder, funded by the Loulou Foundation, Baylor College of Medicine and the Jan and Dan Duncan Neurological Research Institute (NRI) at [[Texas Children's Hospital|Texas Children\u2019s Hospital]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bcm.edu/news/research/research-focuses-on-cdkl5-deficiency|title=Research collaboration focuses on CDKL5 Deficiency Disorder|last=Gutierrez|first=Graciela|date=Oct 30, 2019|website=Baylor College of Medicine Research News|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Spinocerebellar ataxia type 1 ===\nFollowing the establishment of her own lab, Zoghbi continued studying [[spinocerebellar ataxia type 1]] (SCA1), in collaboration with Harry Orr from the [[University of Minnesota]]. On the same day, 8 April 1993, both Zoghbi and Orr identified [[Ataxin 1|ATXN1]] as the gene responsible for SCA1.<ref name=\"jci\"/> They determined that the disease was caused by an [[trinucleotide repeat expansion|expansion]] of the [[glutamine]]-encoding CAG trinucleotide repeat in this gene, and that the younger the age of onset, the longer the CAG repeat.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Orr, Harry T.|author2=Chung, Ming-yi|author3=Banfi, Sandro|author4=Kwiatkowski Jr., Thomas J.|author5=Servadio, Antonio|author6=Beaudet, Arthur L.|author7=McCall, Alanna E.|author8=Duvick, Lisa A.|author9=Ranum, Laura P. W.|author10=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|title=Expansion of an unstable trinucleotide CAG repeat in spinocerebellar ataxia type 1|journal=[[Nature Genetics]]|date=1 Jul 1993|volume=4|issue=3|pages=221\u2013226|doi=10.1038/ng0793-221|pmid=8358429}}</ref>  Further work by Zoghbi, Orr and their teams demonstrated that the [[protein folding|misfolding]], aggregation, and [[proteasome|proteasomal]] [[proteolysis|degradation]] of the [[protein]] product of this gene, [[Ataxin 1]], played a role in the disorder.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Cummings, Christopher J.|author2=Mancini, Michael A.|author3=Antalffy, Barbara|author4=DeFranco, Donald B.|author5=Orr, Harry T.|author6=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|title=Chaperone suppression of aggregation and altered subcellular proteasome localization imply protein misfolding in SCA1|journal=Nature Genetics|date=1 Jun 1998|volume=19|issue=2|pages=148\u2013154|doi=10.1038/502|pmid=9620770}}</ref>\n\n=== Math1 ===\nAfter solving the [[etiology]] of [[spinocerebellar ataxia type 1]], Zoghbi began studying animal genes related to [[balance (ability)|balance]]. As Baylor's [[Hugo J. Bellen]] described the role of the ''atonal'' gene in balance in [[Drosophila melanogaster|fruit flies]], Zoghbi chose to study its [[mammal]]ian [[sequence homology|homolog]].  A member of her lab successfully cloned the mouse homolog, ''[[ATOH1|Math1]]'', in 1996.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Ben-Arie, Nissim|author2=McCall, Alanna E.|author3=Berkman, Scott|author4=Eichele, Gregor|author5=Bellen, Hugo J.|author6=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|title=Evolutionary conservation of sequence and expression of the bHLH protein Atonal suggests a conserved role in neurogenesis|journal=[[Human Molecular Genetics]]|date=1 Sep 1996|volume=5|issue=9|pages=1207\u20131216|doi=10.1093/hmg/5.9.1207|pmid=8872459|doi-access=free}}</ref> Her team went on to find that, in addition to its involvement in balance and coordination, ''Math1'' is also crucial to hearing <ref>{{cite journal|author1=Bermingham, Nessan A.|author2=Hassan, Bassem A.|author3=Price, Steven D.|author4=Vollrath, Melissa A.|author5=Ben-Arie, Nissim|author6=Eatock, Ruth A.|author7=Bellen, Hugo J.|author8=Lysakowski, Anna|author9=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|title=Math1: An Essential Gene for the Generation of Inner Ear Hair Cells|journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]]|date=11 Jun 1999|volume=284|issue=5421|pages=1837\u20131841|doi=10.1126/science.284.5421.1837|pmid=10364557}}</ref> and the formation of secretory cells in the gut.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Yang, Qi|author2=Bermingham, Nessan A.|author3=Finegold, Milton J.|author4=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|title=Requirement of Math1 for secretory cell lineage commitment in the mouse intestine|journal=Science|date=7 Dec 2001|volume=294|issue=5549|pages=2155\u20132158|doi=10.1126/science.1065718|pmid=11739954}}</ref> Her lab has also shown that aberrant activation of ''Math1'' could lead to [[medulloblastoma]], a common childhood brain tumor, and that mice which did not express ''Math1,'' did not develop the tumor.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Flora|first1=Adriano|last2=Klisch|first2=Tiemo J.|last3=Schuster|first3=Gabriele|last4=Zoghbi|first4=Huda Y.|title=Deletion of Atoh1 Disrupts Sonic Hedgehog Signaling in the Developing Cerebellum and Prevents Medulloblastoma|journal=Science|date=4 Dec 2009|volume=326|issue=5958|pages=1424\u20131427|doi=10.1126/science.1181453|pmid=19965762|pmc=3638077}}</ref>\n\n===Rett syndrome===\n\nEver since Zoghbi was introduced to [[Rett syndrome]] early in her career, she has been working on the disorder alongside other research, despite the lack of enthusiasm from her colleagues, fellow researchers and funding agencies. The main reason is that very few individuals and even fewer families are available for investigation. In the 1990s, she collaborated with [[Uta Francke]] from [[Stanford University]] to identify the gene responsible for Rett syndrome. In 1992, she narrowed down the target to a section of the [[X chromosome]].<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Ellison, Kimberley A.|author2=Fill, Carolyn P.|author3=Terwilliger, Joseph|author4=DeGennaro, Louis J.|author5=Martin-Gallardo, Antonia|author6=Anvret, Maria|author7=Percy, Alan K.|author8=Ott, Jurg|author9=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|title=Examination of X chromosome markers in Rett syndrome: exclusion mapping with a novel variation on multilocus linkage analysis|journal=[[American Journal of Human Genetics]]|date=Feb 1992|volume=50|issue=2|pages=278\u2013287|pmid=1734712|pmc=1682446}}</ref> In 1999, a [[postdoctoral researcher]] in Zoghbi's lab identified [[MECP2]] as the causative gene.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Amir, Ruthie E.|author2=Van den Veyver, Ignatia B.|author3=Wan, Mimi|author4=Tran, Charles Q.|author5=Francke, Uta|author6=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|title=Rett syndrome is caused by mutations in X-linked MECP2, encoding methyl-CpG-binding protein 2|journal=Nature Genetics|date=1 Oct 1999|volume=23|issue=2|pages=185\u2013188|doi=10.1038/13810|pmid=10508514}}</ref> The MECP2 [[protein]] binds [[DNA methylation|methylated]] [[cytosine]] ([[5-methylcytosine]]) in [[CpG sites]], and is indispensable for almost all [[brain cells]].<ref name=\"jci\"/> In the paper, she and her team demonstrated that Rett syndrome was an [[X-linked dominant inheritance|X-linked dominant]] disorder, meaning that when 1 of the 2 copies of the MECP2 gene is abnormal, Rett syndrome will result.<ref name=\"jax\"/>\n\nZoghbi's team keeps studying MECP2, and discovered in 2004 that overexpressing the protein in mouse led to an [[autism]]-like neurological disorder.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Collins, Ann L.|author2=Levenson, Jonathan M.|author3=Vilaythong, Alexander P.|author4=Richman, Ronald|author5=Armstrong, Dawna L.|author6=Noebels, Jeffrey L.|author7=Sweatt, J. David|author8=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|title=Mild overexpression of MeCP2 causes a progressive neurological disorder in mice|journal=Human Molecular Genetics|date=6 Sep 2004|volume=13|issue=21|pages=2679\u20132689|doi=10.1093/hmg/ddh282|pmid=15351775|doi-access=free}}</ref> In 2009, she found mice deficient of the Mecp2 gene (the mouse homolog of human MECP2) had lower levels of [[norepinephrine]], [[dopamine]] and [[serotonin]],<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Samaco, Rodney C.|author2=Mandel-Brehm, Caleigh|author3=Chao, Hsiao-Tuan|author4=Ward, Christopher S.|author5=Fyffe-Maricich, Sharyl L.|author6=Ren, Jun|author7=Hyland, Keith |author8=Thaller, Christina |author9=Maricich, Stephen M.|author10=Humphreys, Peter |author11=Greer, John J.|author12=Percy, Alan|author13=Glaze, Daniel G.|author14=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|author15=Neul, Jeffrey L.|title=Loss of MeCP2 in aminergic neurons causes cell-autonomous defects in neurotransmitter synthesis and specific behavioral abnormalities|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|date=22 Dec 2009|volume=106|issue=51|pages=21966\u201321971|doi=10.1073/pnas.0912257106|pmid=20007372|pmc=2799790}}</ref> consistent with her clinical observations of patients of Rett syndrome in 1985. Recently, Zoghbi confirmed that the MECP2 protein also bound 5-methylcytosine not in CpG sites,<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Chen, Lin|author2=Chen, Kaifu|author3=Lavery, Laura A.|author4=Baker, Steven A.|author5=Shaw, Chad A.|author6=Li, Wei|author7=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|title=MeCP2 binds to non-CG methylated DNA as neurons mature, influencing transcription and the timing of onset for Rett syndrome|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|date=28 Apr 2015|volume=112|issue=17|pages=5509\u20135514|doi=10.1073/pnas.1505909112|pmid=25870282|pmc=4418849}}</ref> and that restoring the level of MECP2 protein in a subset of [[neurons]] was sufficient to rescue some symptoms of Rett syndrome.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Ure, Kerstin|author2=Lu, Hui|author3=Wang, Wei|author4=Ito-Ishida, Aya|author5=Wu, Zhenyu|author6=He, Ling-jie|author7=Sztainberg, Yehezkel|author8=Chen, Wu|author9=Tang, Jianrong|author10=Zoghbi, Huda Y.|title=Restoration of Mecp2 expression in GABAergic neurons is sufficient to rescue multiple disease features in a mouse model of Rett syndrome|journal=[[eLife]]|date=21 Jun 2016|volume=5|pages=e14198|doi=10.7554/eLife.14198|pmid=27328321|pmc=4946897}}</ref>\n\n=== Ataxin-1 link to Alzheimer's ===\nAfter linking the gene Ataxin-1 to SCA1, Zoghbi's lab was approached by Dr. Jaehong Suh of the [[Massachusetts General Hospital|Massachusetts General Hospita]]<nowiki/>l's MassGeneral Institute for Neurodegenerative Disease to investigate the connection between ataxin-1 gene and [[Alzheimer's disease|Alzheimer\u2019s disease]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.bcm.edu/2019/09/05/from-the-labs-ataxin-1-one-gene-two-different-neurodegenerative-diseases/|title=Ataxin-1: One gene, two different neurodegenerative diseases|last=Rodr\u00edguez|first=Ana Mar\u00eda|date=September 5, 2019|website=Baylor College of Medicine, From the Labs|access-date=}}</ref> The subsequent study found that loss of ataxin-1 elevates BACE1 expression and A\u03b2 pathology in mouse models, rendering it a potential contributor to risk and pathogenesis of Alzheimer's disease.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Suh|first=Jaehong|date=22 August 2019|title=Loss of Ataxin-1 Potentiates Alzheimer\u2019s Pathogenesis by Elevating Cerebral BACE1 Transcription|url=https://www.cell.com/cell/fulltext/S0092-8674(19)30843-8|journal=Cell|volume=Volume 178, Issue 5|pages=1159-1175.e17|via=Elsevier Science Direct}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n* [[The Brain Prize|Brain Prize]] (2020)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lundbeckfonden.com/en/thebrainprize/winners/|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n* Victor A. McKusick Leadership Award, [[American Society of Human Genetics]] (2019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ashg.org/awards/awards_2019winners.shtml|title=2019 ASHG Award Recipients {{!}} ASHG|website=www.ashg.org|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref>\n*Member of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] (2018)<ref>{{cite web|title=Dr. Huda Y. Zoghbi|url=https://www.amacad.org/content/system/search.aspx?t=50&s=zoghbi|publisher=[[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]|accessdate=14 Dec 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206001545/https://www.amacad.org/content/system/search.aspx?t=50&s=zoghbi|archive-date=6 December 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Ross Prize in Molecular Medicine, [[Molecular Medicine (journal)|Molecular Medicine]] (2018)<ref>{{cite press release|last=|first=|date=8 Mar 2018|title=Molecular Medicine awards Ross Prize to Baylor College of Medicine's Huda Zoghbi|url=https://www.feinsteininstitute.org/2018/03/molecular-medicine-awards-ross-prize-to-baylor-college-of-medicines-huda-zoghbi/|location=|publisher=[[Feinstein Institute for Medical Research]]|agency=|access-date=14 Dec 2018}}</ref>\n* [[National Order of the Cedar]], [[Lebanon]] (2018)<ref>{{cite news|title=Dr. Huda Zoghbi receives Lebanon's highest honor|url=https://nri.texaschildrens.org/news/dr-huda-zoghbi-receives-lebanons-highest-honor|accessdate=14 Dec 2018|publisher=Jan and Dan Duncan Neurological Research Institute|date=23 Jan 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Breakthrough Prize in Life Sciences]] (2017)<ref>{{cite web|title=Breakthrough Prize Life Sciences Laureates 2017|url=https://breakthroughprize.org/Laureates/2/P1/Y2017|publisher=[[Breakthrough Prize|Break Prize Foundation]]|accessdate=14 Dec 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Gairdner Foundation International Award|Canada Gairdner International Award]] (2017)<ref>{{cite web|title=Huda Y Zoghbi|url=https://gairdner.org/winners/index-of-winners/?_sfm_winner_type=Canada%20Gairdner%20International%20Award&_sfm_winner_year=1959+2020#Huda_Y_Zoghbi|publisher=[[Gairdner Foundation International Award|Gairdner Foundation]]|accessdate=14 Dec 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Jessie Stevenson Kovalenko Medal]] (2016)<ref>{{cite web|title=Jessie Stevenson Kovalenko Medal|url=http://www.nasonline.org/programs/awards/kovalenko-medal.html|publisher=[[National Academy of Sciences]]|accessdate=14 Dec 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Shaw Prize|Shaw Prize in Life Science and Medicine]] (2016)\n* Mechthild Esser Nemmers Prize in [[Medical Science]], [[Northwestern University]] (2015)\n* Vanderbilt Prize in Biomedical Science, [[Vanderbilt University School of Medicine]] (2015)\n* Javits [[Neuroscience]] Investigator Award, [[National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke]] (NINDS), [[National Institutes of Health]] (2015)\n* American Task Force for Lebanon Award (2015)\n* [[Mortimer Sackler|Mortimer D. Sackler, M.D.]] Prize for Distinguished Achievement in [[Developmental Psychobiology]], [[Weill Cornell Medicine]] and [[Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons]] (2015)<ref name=\"viictr\">{{cite web|title=Huda Yahya Zoghbi|url=https://profiles.viictr.org/display/267945|publisher=Virtually Integrated Institutions for Clinical and Translational Research|accessdate=14 Dec 2018}}</ref>\n* Honorary Doctor of Medical Sciences, [[Yale University]] (2014)<ref>{{cite news|title=Yale awards 12 honorary degrees at 2014 graduation|url=https://news.yale.edu/2014/05/19/yale-awards-12-honorary-degrees-2014-graduation|accessdate=14 Dec 2018|publisher=[[Yale University]]|date=19 May 2014}}</ref>\n* [[March of Dimes]] Prize in [[Developmental Biology]] (2014)\n* Edward M. Scolnick Prize in Neuroscience, [[McGovern Institute for Brain Research]], [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (2014)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jennings|first1=Charles|title=McGovern Institute to honor neurogenetics researcher Huda Zoghbi|url=http://mcgovern.mit.edu/news/news/mcgovern-institute-to-honor-neurogenetics-researcher-huda-zoghbi/|accessdate=14 Dec 2018|publisher=[[McGovern Institute for Brain Research]]|date=4 Mar 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Dickson Prize|Dickson Prize in Medicine]], [[University of Pittsburgh]] (2013)\n* [[Pearl Meister Greengard Prize]], [[Rockefeller University]] (2013)\n* [[Gruber Prize in Neuroscience]] (2011)<ref name=\"baylor\"/>\n* Vita and Lee Lyman Dewey Tuttle Brookwood Legacy Award for Excellence and Partnership in Medicine, Brookwood Community (2011)<ref>{{cite news|title=Texas Children's Hospital Neuroscientist Dr. Huda Zoghbi Receives 2011 Legacy Award from The Brookwood Community|url=https://www.texaschildrens.org/about-us/news/releases/texas-childrens-hospital-neuroscientist-dr-huda-zoghbi-receives-2011-legacy|accessdate=14 Dec 2018|publisher=[[Texas Children's Hospital]]}}</ref>\n* International [[Rett Syndrome]] Foundation's Circle of Angels Research Award (2009)\n* Vilcek Prize for Biomedical Research, [[The Vilcek Foundation|Vilcek Foundation]] (2009)\n* Marion Spencer Fay Award, [[Drexel University College of Medicine]] (2009)<ref name=\"baylor\"/>\n* Cathedra Laboris, [[University of Monterrey]] (2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.udem.edu.mx/Eng/VIAC/Pages/DICSA/catedra-laboris.aspx|title=Cathedra Laboris|publisher=[[University of Monterrey]]|access-date=September 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913045210/http://www.udem.edu.mx/Eng/VIAC/Pages/DICSA/catedra-laboris.aspx|archive-date=September 13, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Honorary Doctor of Science, [[Meharry Medical College]] (2008)\n* [[Texas Women's Hall of Fame]] (2008)<ref name=\"baylor\"/>\n* [[Perl-UNC Prize|Perl-UNC Neuroscience Prize]] (2007)<ref>{{cite news|title=Baylor College scientist wins Perl-UNC Neuroscience Prize|url=http://www.med.unc.edu/www/newsarchive/2008/may/baylor-college-scientist-wins-perl-unc-neuroscience-prize|accessdate=14 Dec 2018|publisher=[[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]]|date=20 May 2008}}</ref>\n* Massachusetts Institute of Technology Arab Students' Organization [[Science]] and [[Technology]] Lifetime Achievement Award (2007)<ref>{{cite news|title=Arab Students' Organization hosts awards|url=https://news.mit.edu/2007/arab-sci-tech|accessdate=3 Dec 2018|publisher=[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]|date=12 Apr 2007}}</ref>\n* Honorary Doctor of Science, [[Middlebury College]] (2007)\n* [[Robert J. and Claire Pasarow Foundation Medical Research Award|Robert J. and Claire Pasarow Foundation Award in Neuropsychiatry Research]] (2007)\n* Member of the [[National Academy of Sciences]] (2004)\n* Neuronal Plasticity Prize, [[Ipsen|Ipsen Foundation]] (2004)\n* Marta Philipson Award in Pediatrics, Philipson Foundation for Research (2004)<ref name=\"baylor\"/>\n* Fellow of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] (2002)\n* Raymond D. Adams Lectureship, [[American Neurological Association]] (2002)<ref name=\"viictr\"/>\n* [[Bernard Sachs]] Award, Society for Pediatric Research (2001)\n* Member of the [[National Academy of Medicine]] (formerly the Institute of Medicine) (2000)\n* Sidney Carter Award, [[American Academy of Neurology]] (1998)\n* Soriano Lectureship, [[American Neurological Association]] (1998)\n* Javits Award, [[NINDS]], National Institutes of Health (1998)\n* [[E. Mead Johnson Award]], Society of Pediatric Research (1996)\n* Kilby International Award (1995)<ref name=\"baylor\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nZoghbi met her husband, [[William Zoghbi]] when they were medical students in the [[American University of Beirut]]. In 1977, she continued her medical school study in [[Meharry Medical College]], and William transferred to Meharry next year. They both had their residencies in the [[Baylor College of Medicine]] after graduation. They married in 1980 and have 2 children.<ref name=\"shawautobio\"/> William is the chief of the Department of [[Cardiology]] at [[Houston Methodist Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web|title=William A. Zoghbi, MD, FASE, FAHA, MACC|url=https://www.houstonmethodist.org/faculty/william-zoghbi/|publisher=[[Houston Methodist Hospital]]|accessdate=14 Dec 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Scholia|author}}\n*{{Charlie Rose view|15433}}\n*{{Worldcat id|lccn-n93-802498}}\n\n{{Shaw Prize laureates}}\n{{Texas Women's Hall of Fame}}\n{{Breakthrough Prize laureates}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zoghbi, Huda}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Howard Hughes Medical Investigators]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Academy of Medicine]]\n[[Category:Baylor College of Medicine faculty]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:American neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:Lebanese pediatricians]]\n[[Category:Lebanese neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:Lebanese women neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:Lebanese women scientists]]\n[[Category:People from Beirut]]\n[[Category:American women neuroscientists]]\n", "name_user": "Jarszick", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Huda_Zoghbi"}
{"title_page": "Pasadena Star-News", "text_new": "[[File:Seal_of_Pasadena,_California.png|thumb|Seal of Pasadena California ]]\nThe '''''Pasadena Star-News''''' is a paid local daily newspaper for the greater [[Pasadena, California]] area. The Pasadena ''Star-News'' is a member of Southern California News Group<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hagen|first1=Ryan|url=http://www.sbsun.com/media/20160321/what-is-digital-first-media-and-the-southern-california-news-group-who-just-purchased-the-orange-county-register|title=What is Digital First Media and the Southern California News Group who just purchased the Orange County Register?|newspaper=[[San Bernardino Sun]]|accessdate=4 April 2016}}</ref>(formerly the [[Los Angeles Newspaper Group]]), since 1996. It is also part of the San Gabriel Valley Newspaper Group, along with the ''[[San Gabriel Valley Tribune]]'' and the ''[[Whittier Daily News]]''.\n\nThe Pasadena Star-News is known for its local news coverage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/2019/10/25/scng-gets-google-funding-for-news-innovation-project/|title=About us|website=Pasadena Star News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> The news group publishes new stories and updates around the clock, online on their website as well as seven days a week daily print newspapers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/2019/10/25/scng-gets-google-funding-for-news-innovation-project/|title=About us|website=Pasadena Star News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Active on both [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]], digital delivery has become a priority for the Pasadena Star-News group over the last decade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/2019/10/25/scng-gets-google-funding-for-news-innovation-project/|title=About us|website=Pasadena Star News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Keeping updated and relevant for its users.{{Infobox newspaper\n| name                 = Pasadena Star-News\n| logo                 = \n| image                = \n| caption              = \n| type                 = Daily newspaper\n| format               = [[Broadsheet]]\n| owners               = [[Digital First Media]]\n| founder              = \n| publisher            = Ron Hasse\n| editor               = Frank Pine\n| chiefeditor          = \n| assoceditor          = \n| maneditor            = \n| newseditor           = \n| managingeditordesign = \n| campuseditor         = \n| campuschief          = \n| opeditor             = \n| sportseditor         = \n| photoeditor          = \n| staff                = \n| foundation           = \n| political            = \n| language             = English\n| ceased publication   = \n| headquarters         = 2 N. Lake Ave. Suite 150<br/> [[Pasadena, California]] 91101\n| circulation          = \n| sister newspapers    = ''[[Los Angeles Daily News]]'' <br>''[[San Gabriel Valley Tribune]]''<br>''[[Whittier Daily News]]''\n| ISSN                 = \n| oclc                 = \n| website              = {{URL|http://pasadenastarnews.com/|pasadenastarnews.com}}\n}}\n\n== History ==\nFirst published in 1884, the paper was originally located at the corner of Colorado Boulevard and Oakland Avenue for years. That building is now home to [[Le Cordon Bleu|Technique at Le Cordon Bleu College of Culinary Arts]] and [[24 Hour Fitness]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/2017/09/15/pasadena-star-news-information-and-history/|title=Pasadena Star-News Information and History|date=2017-09-15|website=Pasadena Star News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>The first radio broadcast of the [[Rose Parade]] in 1926 aired out of a pair of radio towers that the building once hosted the broadcast of Pasadena Star-News programming under the call sign KPSN. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/2017/09/15/pasadena-star-news-information-and-history/|title=Pasadena Star-News Information and History|date=2017-09-15|website=Pasadena Star News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>From 1904-1956 [[Charles H. Prisk]], was one of the first publishers and owner of the Pasadena Star-News. Charles was also the owner of the Pasadena Post and the Long Beach Press-Telegram, [[William F. Prisk]], his brother was a publisher. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/2017/09/15/pasadena-star-news-information-and-history/|title=Pasadena Star-News Information and History|date=2017-09-15|website=Pasadena Star News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>[[William Paddock]], Prisk's son-in-law was the vice president and general manager of the Star-News, Pasadena-Post and the Press-Telegram<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/2017/09/15/pasadena-star-news-information-and-history/|title=Pasadena Star-News Information and History|date=2017-09-15|website=Pasadena Star News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. Willam Paddock married Prisk's daughter Neva Prisk Malaby then began working at the newspapers as a result. William Paddock also known as [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] Champion Charles \"Charley\" ran the world record for the [[100-yard dash]] in 1921 at 9.5 seconds, giving him the title \"World's Fastest Human\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/2017/09/15/pasadena-star-news-information-and-history/|title=Pasadena Star-News Information and History|date=2017-09-15|website=Pasadena Star News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> Editors in the historical Star-News Building included Ed Essertier, Charles Cherniss, Bill Winter, Larry Wilson, and Frank Girardot. Publishers after Bernard J. Ridder included Bill Applebee.\n\nRidder Newspapers bought the ''Star-News''in 1956<ref name=\"lat-1956mar262\">{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/doc/166924759.html|title=Ridder Buys Both Papers in Pasadena|date=March 26, 1956|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|page=15|quote=Ridder Publications have bought both Pasadena daily newspapers, the Star-News and the Indenendent. The announcement was made Jointly yesterday by Ridder executives and by W.F. Prisk, publisher of the evening Star-News, and E.D. Bates and Fred Runyon, publisher and co-owner, respectively, of the morning Independent. The Star-News will continue in the evening field, Ridder officials said. The Independent will continue in the morning field. But the two will combine their Sunday editions.|url-access=subscription}} [https://search.proquest.com/docview/166924759/ Alternate Link] via [[ProQuest]].</ref>and [[Bernard J. Ridder]]<nowiki/>took over as publisher. Ridder merged with Knight to form [[Knight Ridder]]<nowiki/>in 1974. The paper was sold off in 1989 to a company owned by [[William Dean Singleton]];<ref name=\"lat-1989apr202\">{{cite news|last=White|first=George|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1989-04-20/business/fi-2454_1_knight-ridder-newspaper-chain-monrovia-news-post-foothill-intercity-newspapers|title=Singleton to Pay $55 Million for the Pasadena Star-News|date=April 20, 1989|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|page=OC_C1}} [https://search.proquest.com/docview/1149860130/ Alternate Link] via [[ProQuest]].</ref>the [[Thomson Corporation]] bought majority control of the paper a year later.<ref name=\"lat-1990aug222\">{{cite news|last=Hudson|first=Berkley|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-08-22/business/fi-1108_1_pasadena-star-news|title=Pasadena Star-News Sold to Unit of Canadian Chain|date=August 22, 1990|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref>Thomson sold the ''Star-News'' to Singleton's [[MediaNews Group]]<nowiki/>in 1996,<ref name=\"lat-1996oct312\">{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-10-31/business/fi-59637_1_san-gabriel-valley-tribune|title=San Gabriel Valley Papers Lay Off 31 People|date=October 31, 1996|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref>which went on to become part of the Los Angeles Newspaper Group.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/leavingreadersbe00robe|title=Leaving Readers Behind: The Age of Corporate Newspapering|date=2001|publisher=[[University of Arkansas Press]]|isbn=1610752325|editor1-last=Roberts|editor1-first=Gene|editor1-link=Gene Roberts (journalist)|location=[[Fayetteville, Arkansas|Fayetteville]]|accessdate=|editor2-last=Kunkel|editor2-first=Thomas|editor2-link=|editor3-last=Layton|editor3-first=Charles|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\nThe newspaper also publishes the ''Rose Magazine''which provides coverage of the Tournament of Roses Parade and the Rose Bowl Game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/2019/10/25/scng-gets-google-funding-for-news-innovation-project/|title=About us|website=Pasadena Star News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Social events and Pasadena history==\nPatt Diroll, writes a weekly social events column with photos and a calendar listing on Mondays and editorial board member Larry Wilson writes a column on Pasadena history and current events on Wednesdays.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Coverage area ==\nCoverage area for the [https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/news/ ''Pasadena Star-News''] include:\n\n*[https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/location/california/los-angeles-county/san-gabriel-valley/pasadena/ Pasadena]\n*[https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/location/california/los-angeles-county/san-gabriel-valley/alhambra/ Alhambra]\n*[https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/location/california/los-angeles-county/san-gabriel-valley/altadena/ Altadena]\n*[https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/location/california/los-angeles-county/san-gabriel-valley/monrovia/ Monrovia]\n*[https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/location/california/los-angeles-county/san-gabriel-valley/monterey-park/ Monterey Park]\n*[https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/location/california/los-angeles-county/san-gabriel-valley/arcadia/ Arcadia]\n*[https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/location/california/los-angeles-county/san-gabriel-valley/duarte/ Duarte]\n*[https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/location/california/los-angeles-county/san-gabriel-valley/san-gabriel/ San Gabriel]\n*[https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/location/california/los-angeles-county/san-gabriel-valley/san-marino/ San Marino]\n*[https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/location/california/los-angeles-county/san-gabriel-valley/sierra-madre/ Sierra Madre]\n*[https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/location/california/los-angeles-county/san-gabriel-valley/south-pasadena/ South Pasadena]\n*[https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/location/california/los-angeles-county/san-gabriel-valley/rosemead/ Rosemead]\n*[https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/location/california/los-angeles-county/san-gabriel-valley/el-monte/ El Monte]\n*[https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/location/california/los-angeles-county/san-gabriel-valley/south-el-monte/ South El Monte]\n*[https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/location/california/los-angeles-county/los-angeles/ Los Angeles]\n*[https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/location/california/los-angeles-county/ Los Angeles Country]\n*[https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/location/california/los-angeles-county/san-gabriel-valley/temple-city/ Temple City]\n\n== Previous owners ==\n\n* [[Charles H. Prisk]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/2017/09/15/pasadena-star-news-information-and-history/|title=Pasadena Star-News Information and History|date=2017-09-15|website=Pasadena Star News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n* [[William F. Prisk]]\n\n== Awards ==\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/media/20150509/pasadena-star-news-takes-home-four-statewide-journalism-awards|title=Pasadena Star News takes home four statewide journalism awards|date=2015-05-10|website=Pasadena Star News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>The [[California Newspaper Publishers Association|California Newspapers Publishers Association]] awarded the Pasadena Star-News four of the top journalism awards out of thirty-eight awards given to its parent company Los Angeles News Group at the annual awards luncheon in [[San Diego]].\n\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/2017/09/15/pasadena-star-news-information-and-history/|title=Pasadena Star-News Information and History|date=2017-09-15|website=Pasadena Star News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>The [[California Newspaper Publishers Association|California Newspaper Publisher Association]], the state's press association, named the Pasadena Star-News, California's best mid-sized daily in 2015.\n\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/pages/category/Newspaper/pasadenastarnews/about/|title=Pasadena Star News|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>Winner of the California Newspaper Association's award given for best website.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://pasadenastarnews.com ''Pasadena Star-News'' website]\n\n{{MediaNews Group}}\n{{Pasadena, California}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pasadena Star-News}}\n[[Category:Daily newspapers published in Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Mass media in Pasadena, California]]\n[[Category:MediaNews Group publications]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1905]]\n\n\n{{California-newspaper-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Seal_of_Pasadena,_California.png|thumb|Seal of Pasadena California ]]\nThe '''''Pasadena Star-News''''' is a paid local daily newspaper for the greater [[Pasadena, California]] area. The Pasadena ''Star-News'' is a member of Southern California News Group<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hagen|first1=Ryan|url=http://www.sbsun.com/media/20160321/what-is-digital-first-media-and-the-southern-california-news-group-who-just-purchased-the-orange-county-register|title=What is Digital First Media and the Southern California News Group who just purchased the Orange County Register?|newspaper=[[San Bernardino Sun]]|accessdate=4 April 2016}}</ref>(formerly the [[Los Angeles Newspaper Group]]), since 1996. It is also part of the San Gabriel Valley Newspaper Group, along with the ''[[San Gabr